# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p01] Born as a subject to the Kingdom of Württemberg, part of the German Empire, Einstein moved to Switzerland in 1895, forsaking his citizenship the following year.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p01] In 1896, at the age of seventeen, he enrolled in the mathematics and physics teaching diploma program at the Swiss federal polytechnic school in Zurich, graduating in 1900.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p01] He acquired Swiss citizenship a year later, which he kept for the rest of his life, and afterwards secured a permanent position at the Swiss Patent Office in Bern.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p01] In 1905, he submitted a successful PhD dissertation to the University of Zurich.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p01] In 1914, he moved to Berlin to join the Prussian Academy of Sciences and the Humboldt University of Berlin, becoming director of the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute for Physics in 1917; he also became a Prussian and consequently also German citizen again.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p01] In 1933, while Einstein was visiting the United States, Adolf Hitler came to power in Germany.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p01] Horrified by the Nazi persecution of his fellow Jews, he decided to remain in the US, and was granted American citizenship in 1940.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p01] On the eve of World War II, he endorsed a letter to President Franklin D.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p01] Roosevelt alerting him to the potential German nuclear weapons program and recommending that the US begin similar research, later carried out as the Manhattan Project.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p01] In 1905, sometimes described as his *annus mirabilis* (miracle year), he published four groundbreaking papers.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p01] In them, he outlined a theory of the photoelectric effect, explained Brownian motion, introduced his special theory of relativity, and demonstrated that if the special theory is correct, mass and energy are equivalent to each other.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p01] In 1915, he proposed a general theory of relativity that extended his system of mechanics to incorporate gravitation.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p01] A paper that he published the following year laid out the implications of general relativity for the modeling of the structure and evolution of the universe as a whole.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p01] It introduced the cosmological constant and is further regarded as the first step in the field of modern theoretical cosmology.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p01] In the middle part of his career, Einstein made important contributions to statistical mechanics and quantum theory.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p01] Especially notable was his work on the quantum physics of radiation, in which light consists of particles, subsequently called photons.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p01] With physicist Satyendra Nath Bose, he laid the groundwork for Bose–Einstein statistics.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p01] For much of the last phase of his academic life, Einstein worked on two endeavors that ultimately proved unsuccessful.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p01] First, he advocated against quantum theory's introduction of fundamental randomness into science's picture of the world, objecting that "God does not play dice".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p01] Second, he attempted to devise a unified field theory by generalizing his geometric theory of gravitation to include electromagnetism.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p01] As a result, he became increasingly isolated from mainstream modern physics.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p01] Many things are named after him, including the element Einsteinium.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p01] In 1999, he was named *Time*'s Person of the Century.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein was born in Ulm as a subject to the Kingdom of Württemberg in the German Empire on 14 March 1879.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] His parents, secular Ashkenazi Jews, were Hermann Einstein, a salesman and engineer, and Pauline Koch.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] In 1880, the family moved to Munich's borough of Ludwigsvorstadt-Isarvorstadt, where Einstein's father and his uncle Jakob founded Elektrotechnische Fabrik J.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein & Cie, a company that manufactured electrical equipment based on direct current.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] When he was very young, his parents worried that he had a learning disability because he was very slow to learn to talk.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] When he was five and sick in bed, his father brought him a compass.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] This sparked his lifelong fascination with electromagnetism.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Peter's Catholic elementary school in Munich from the age of five.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] When he was eight, he was transferred to the Luitpold Gymnasium, where he received advanced primary and then secondary school education.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] In 1894, Hermann and Jakob's company tendered for a contract to install electric lighting in Munich, but without success—they lacked the capital that would have been required to update their technology from direct current to the more efficient, alternating current alternative.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] The failure of their bid forced them to sell their Munich factory and search for new opportunities elsewhere.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] The Einstein family moved to Italy, first to Milan and a few months later to Pavia, where they settled in Palazzo Cornazzani.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein, then fifteen, stayed behind in Munich in order to finish his schooling.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] His father wanted him to study electrical engineering, but he was a fractious pupil who found the Gymnasium's regimen and teaching methods far from congenial.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] He later wrote that the school's policy of strict rote learning was harmful to creativity.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] At the end of December 1894, a letter from a doctor persuaded the Luitpold's authorities to release him from its care, and he joined his family in Pavia.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] While in Italy as a teenager, he wrote an essay titled "On the Investigation of the State of the Ether in a Magnetic Field".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein excelled at physics and mathematics from an early age, and soon acquired the mathematical expertise normally only found in a child several years his senior.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] He began teaching himself algebra, calculus and Euclidean geometry when he was twelve; he made such rapid progress that he discovered an original proof of the Pythagorean theorem before his thirteenth birthday.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] A family tutor, Max Talmud, said that only a short time after he had given the twelve year old Einstein a geometry textbook, the boy "had worked through the whole book.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] He thereupon devoted himself to higher mathematics ...
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Soon the flight of his mathematical genius was so high I could not follow." Einstein recorded that he had "mastered integral and differential calculus" while still just fourteen.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] His love of algebra and geometry was so great that at twelve, he was already confident that nature could be understood as a "mathematical structure".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] At thirteen, when his range of enthusiasms had broadened to include music and philosophy, Talmud introduced Einstein to Kant's *Critique of Pure Reason*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] In 1895, at the age of sixteen, Einstein sat the entrance examination for the federal polytechnic school (later the Eidgenössische Technische Hochschule, ETH) in Zurich, Switzerland.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] He failed to reach the required standard in the general part of the test, but performed with distinction in physics and mathematics.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] On the advice of the polytechnic's principal, he completed his secondary education at the Argovian cantonal school (a gymnasium) in Aarau, Switzerland, graduating in 1896.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] While lodging in Aarau with the family of Jost Winteler, he fell in love with Winteler's daughter, Marie.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] In January 1896, with his father's approval, Einstein renounced his citizenship of the German Kingdom of Württemberg in order to avoid conscription into military service.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] The *Matura* (graduation for the successful completion of higher secondary schooling), awarded to him in September 1896, acknowledged him to have performed well across most of the curriculum, allotting him a top grade of 6 for history, physics, algebra, geometry, and descriptive geometry.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] At seventeen, he enrolled in the four-year mathematics and physics teaching diploma program at the federal polytechnic school.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] He befriended fellow student Marcel Grossmann, who would help him there to get by despite his loose study habits, and later to mathematically underpin his revolutionary insights into physics.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Marie Winteler, a year older than him, took up a teaching post in Olsberg, Switzerland.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] The five other polytechnic school freshmen following the same course as Einstein included just one woman, a twenty year old Serbian, Mileva Marić.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Over the next few years, the pair spent many hours discussing their shared interests and learning about topics in physics that the polytechnic school's lectures did not cover.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] In his letters to Marić, Einstein confessed that exploring science with her by his side was much more enjoyable than reading a textbook in solitude.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Eventually the two students became not only friends, but also lovers.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Historians of physics are divided on the question of the extent to which Marić contributed to the insights of Einstein's *annus mirabilis* publications.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] There is at least some evidence that he was influenced by her scientific ideas, but there are scholars who doubt whether her impact on his thought was of any great significance at all.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Correspondence between Einstein and Marić, discovered and published in 1987, revealed that the couple had a daughter named Lieserl.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] She was born in early 1902 while Marić was visiting her parents in Novi Sad.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] When Marić returned to Switzerland the child was no longer with her.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] In a letter written in September 1903, Einstein suggested that the girl was either given up for adoption or died of scarlet fever in infancy.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein and Marić married in January 1903.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] In May 1904, their son Hans Albert was born in Bern, Switzerland.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Their son Eduard was born in Zurich in July 1910.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] In 1912, Einstein entered into a relationship with Elsa Löwenthal, who was both his first cousin on his mother's side and his second cousin on his father's.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] When Marić learned of his infidelity soon after moving to Berlin with him in April 1914, she returned to Zurich, taking Hans Albert and Eduard with her.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein and Marić were granted a divorce on 14 February 1919 on the grounds of having lived apart for five years.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] As part of the divorce settlement, Einstein agreed that if he were to win a Nobel Prize, he would give the money that he received to Marić; he won the prize two years later.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] In 1923, he began a relationship with a secretary named Betty Neumann, the niece of his close friend Hans Mühsam.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Löwenthal nevertheless remained loyal to him, accompanying him when he emigrated to the United States in 1933.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] In 1935, she was diagnosed with heart and kidney problems.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] A volume of Einstein's letters released by the Hebrew University of Jerusalem in 2006 added some other women with whom he was romantically involved.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] They included Margarete Lebach (a married Austrian), Estella Katzenellenbogen (the rich owner of a florist business), Toni Mendel (a wealthy Jewish widow) and Ethel Michanowski (a Berlin socialite), with whom he spent time and from whom he accepted gifts while married to Löwenthal.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] After being widowed, Einstein was briefly in a relationship with Margarita Konenkova, thought by some to be a Russian spy; her husband, the Russian sculptor Sergei Konenkov, created the bronze bust of Einstein at the Institute for Advanced Study at Princeton.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Following an episode of acute mental illness at about the age of twenty, Einstein's son Eduard was diagnosed with schizophrenia.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] He spent the remainder of his life either in the care of his mother or in temporary confinement in an asylum.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] After her death, he was committed permanently to Burghölzli, the Psychiatric University Hospital in Zurich.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein graduated from the federal polytechnic school in 1900, duly certified as competent to teach mathematics and physics.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] His successful acquisition of Swiss citizenship in February 1901 was not followed by the usual sequel of conscription; the Swiss authorities deemed him medically unfit for military service.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] He found that Swiss schools too appeared to have no use for him, failing to offer him a teaching position despite the almost two years that he spent applying for one.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Eventually it was with the help of Marcel Grossmann's father that he secured a post in Bern at the Swiss Patent Office, as an assistant examiner – level III.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Patent applications that landed on Einstein's desk for his evaluation included ideas for a gravel sorter and an electric typewriter.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] His employers were pleased enough with his work to make his position permanent in 1903, although they did not think that he should be promoted until he had "fully mastered machine technology".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] It is conceivable that his labors at the patent office had a bearing on his development of his special theory of relativity.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] He arrived at his revolutionary ideas about space, time and light through thought experiments about the transmission of signals and the synchronization of clocks, matters which also figured in some of the inventions submitted to him for assessment.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] In 1902, Einstein and his friends Conrad Habicht and Maurice Solovine, whom he had met in Bern, formed a group that held regular meetings to discuss science and philosophy.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Their choice of a name for their club, the Olympia Academy, was an ironic comment upon its far from Olympian status.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Sometimes they were joined by Marić, who limited her participation in their proceedings to careful listening.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] The thinkers whose works they reflected upon included Henri Poincaré, Ernst Mach and David Hume, all of whom significantly influenced Einstein's own subsequent ideas and beliefs.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's first paper, "Folgerungen aus den Capillaritätserscheinungen" ("Conclusions drawn from the phenomena of capillarity"), in which he proposed a model of intermolecular attraction that he afterwards disavowed as worthless, was published in the journal *Annalen der Physik* in 1901.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] His 24-page doctoral dissertation also addressed a topic in molecular physics.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Titled "Eine neue Bestimmung der Moleküldimensionen" ("A New Determination of Molecular Dimensions") and dedicated "Meinem Freunde Herr Dr.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Marcel Grossmann gewidmet" (to his friend Marcel Grossman), it was completed on 30 April 1905 and approved by Professor Alfred Kleiner of the University of Zurich three months later.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] The publications deeply impressed Einstein's contemporaries.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's sabbatical as a civil servant approached its end in 1908, when he secured a junior teaching position at the University of Bern.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] In 1909, a lecture on relativistic electrodynamics that he gave at the University of Zurich, much admired by Alfred Kleiner, led to Zurich's luring him away from Bern with a newly created associate professorship.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Promotion to a full professorship followed in April 1911, when he took up a chair at the German Charles-Ferdinand University in Prague, a move which required him to become an Austrian citizen of the Austro-Hungarian Empire, which was not completed.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] His time in Prague saw him producing eleven research papers.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] From 30 October to 3 November 1911, Einstein attended the first Solvay Conference on Physics.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] In July 1912, he returned to his *alma mater*, the ETH Zurich, to take up a chair in theoretical physics.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] His teaching activities there centered on thermodynamics and analytical mechanics, and his research interests included the molecular theory of heat, continuum mechanics and the development of a relativistic theory of gravitation.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] In his work on the latter topic, he was assisted by his friend Marcel Grossmann, whose knowledge of the kind of mathematics required was greater than his own.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] In the spring of 1913, two German visitors, Max Planck and Walther Nernst, called upon Einstein in Zurich in the hope of persuading him to relocate to Berlin.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Their invitation was all the more appealing to him because Berlin happened to be the home of his latest girlfriend, Elsa Löwenthal.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] He duly joined the Academy on 24 July 1913, and moved into an apartment in the Berlin district of Dahlem on 1 April 1914.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] He was installed in his Humboldt University position shortly thereafter.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] The outbreak of the First World War in July 1914 marked the beginning of Einstein's gradual estrangement from the nation of his birth.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] However, this expression of his doubts about German policy did not prevent him from being elected to a two-year term as president of the German Physical Society in 1916.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] When the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute for Physics opened its doors the following year—its foundation delayed because of the war—Einstein was appointed its first director, just as Planck and Nernst had promised.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein was elected a Foreign Member of the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1920, and a Foreign Member of the Royal Society in 1921.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] In 1922, he was awarded the 1921 Nobel Prize in Physics "for his services to Theoretical Physics, and especially for his discovery of the law of the photoelectric effect".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Bose derived the Planck spectrum in 1924.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] That same year, Einstein was elected an International Honorary Member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Britain's closest equivalent of the Nobel award, the Royal Society's Copley Medal, was not hung around Einstein's neck until 1925.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] He was elected an International Member of the American Philosophical Society in 1930.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein resigned from the Prussian Academy in March 1933.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] His accomplishments in Berlin had included the completion of the general theory of relativity, proving the Einstein–de Haas effect, contributing to the quantum theory of radiation, and the development of Bose–Einstein statistics.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] In 1911, he first calculated the gravitational deflection of light passing close to the Sun, a prediction later adjusted upon completion of the general theory of relativity.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] He reworked his calculation in 1913, having now found a way to model gravitation with the Riemann curvature tensor of a non-Euclidean four-dimensional spacetime.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] A total eclipse of the Sun that took place on 29 May 1919 provided an opportunity to put his theory of gravitational lensing to the test, and observations performed by Sir Arthur Eddington yielded results that were consistent with his calculations.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Eddington's work was reported at length in newspapers around the world.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] On 7 November 1919, for example, the leading British newspaper, *The Times*, printed a banner headline that read: "Revolution in Science – New Theory of the Universe – Newtonian Ideas Overthrown".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein began his new life as an intellectual icon in America, where he arrived on 2 April 1921.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] He was welcomed to New York City by Mayor John Francis Hylan, and then spent three weeks giving lectures and attending receptions.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] He spoke several times at Columbia University and Princeton, and in Washington, he visited the White House with representatives of the National Academy of Sciences.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] He returned to Europe via London, where he was the guest of the philosopher and statesman Viscount Haldane.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] He used his time in the British capital to meet several people prominent in British scientific, political or intellectual life, and to deliver a lecture at King's College.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] In July 1921, he published an essay, "My First Impression of the U.S.A.", in which he sought to sketch the American character.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] He wrote of his transatlantic hosts in highly approving terms: "What strikes a visitor is the joyous, positive attitude to life ...
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] In 1922, Einstein's travels were to the old world rather than the new.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] He devoted six months to a tour of Asia that saw him speaking in Japan, Singapore and Sri Lanka (then known as Ceylon).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] After his first public lecture in Tokyo, he met Emperor Yoshihito and his wife at the Imperial Palace, with thousands of spectators thronging the streets in the hope of catching a glimpse of him.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] (In a letter to his sons, he wrote that Japanese people seemed to him to be generally modest, intelligent and considerate, and to have a true appreciation of art.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] But his picture of them in his diary was less flattering: "[the] intellectual needs of this nation seem to be weaker than their artistic ones – natural disposition?" His journal also contains views of China and India which were uncomplimentary.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Of Chinese people, he wrote that "even the children are spiritless and look obtuse...
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] It would be a pity if these Chinese supplant all other races.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] For the likes of us the mere thought is unspeakably dreary".) He was greeted with even greater enthusiasm on the last leg of his tour, in which he spent twelve days in Mandatory Palestine, newly entrusted to British rule by the League of Nations in the aftermath of the First World War.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Sir Herbert Samuel, the British High Commissioner, welcomed him with a degree of ceremony normally only accorded to a visiting head of state, including a cannon salute.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] One reception held in his honor was stormed by people determined to hear him speak: he told them that he was happy that Jews were beginning to be recognized as a force in the world.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] On April 6, 1922, during a visit to Paris, Einstein engaged in a debate on relativity with the philosopher Henri Bergson.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] This dispute has had widespread ramifications for the humanities and was an academic *cause célèbre* at the time.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's decision to tour the eastern hemisphere in 1922 meant that he was unable to go to Stockholm in the December of that year to participate in the Nobel prize ceremony.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] His place at the traditional Nobel banquet was taken by a German diplomat, who gave a speech praising him not only as a physicist but also as a campaigner for peace.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] A two-week visit to Spain that he undertook in 1923 saw him collecting another award, a membership of the Spanish Academy of Sciences signified by a diploma handed to him by King Alfonso XIII.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] He was appointed as a German delegate rather than as a representative of Switzerland because of the machinations of two Catholic activists, Oskar Halecki and Giuseppe Motta.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] By persuading Secretary General Eric Drummond to deny Einstein the place on the committee reserved for a Swiss thinker, they created an opening for Gonzague de Reynold, who used his League of Nations position as a platform from which to promote traditional Catholic doctrine.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's former physics professor Hendrik Lorentz and the Polish chemist Marie Curie were also members of the committee.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] In March and April 1925, Einstein and his wife visited South America, where they spent about a week in Brazil, a week in Uruguay and a month in Argentina.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] In December 1930, Einstein began another significant sojourn in the United States, drawn back to the US by the offer of a two month research fellowship at the California Institute of Technology.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Caltech supported him in his wish that he should not be exposed to quite as much attention from the media as he had experienced when visiting the US in 1921, and he therefore declined all the invitations to receive prizes or make speeches that his admirers poured down upon him.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] But he remained willing to allow his fans at least some of the time with him that they requested.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] After arriving in New York City, Einstein was taken to various places and events, including Chinatown, a lunch with the editors of *The New York Times*, and a performance of *Carmen* at the Metropolitan Opera, where he was cheered by the audience on his arrival.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] During the days following, he was given the keys to the city by Mayor Jimmy Walker and met Nicholas Murray Butler, the president of Columbia University, who described Einstein as "the ruling monarch of the mind".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Harry Emerson Fosdick, pastor at New York's Riverside Church, gave Einstein a tour of the church and showed him a full-size statue that the church made of Einstein, standing at the entrance.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Also during his stay in New York, he joined a crowd of 15,000 people at Madison Square Garden during a Hanukkah celebration.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein next traveled to California, where he met Caltech president and Nobel laureate Robert A.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] His friendship with Millikan was "awkward", as Millikan "had a penchant for patriotic militarism", where Einstein was a pronounced pacifist.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] During an address to Caltech's students, Einstein noted that science was often inclined to do more harm than good.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] This aversion to war also led Einstein to befriend author Upton Sinclair and film star Charlie Chaplin, both noted for their pacifism.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Carl Laemmle, head of Universal Studios, gave Einstein a tour of his studio and introduced him to Chaplin.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] They had an instant rapport, with Chaplin inviting Einstein and his wife, Elsa, to his home for dinner.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p02] Chaplin said Einstein's outward persona, calm and gentle, seemed to conceal a "highly emotional temperament", from which came his "extraordinary intellectual energy".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Chaplin's film *City Lights* was to premiere a few days later in Hollywood, and Chaplin invited Einstein and Elsa to join him as his special guests.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Walter Isaacson, Einstein's biographer, described this as "one of the most memorable scenes in the new era of celebrity".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Chaplin visited Einstein at his home on a later trip to Berlin and recalled his "modest little flat" and the piano at which he had begun writing his theory.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Chaplin speculated that it was "possibly used as kindling wood by the Nazis".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein and Chaplin were cheered at the premiere of the film.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] In February 1933, while on a visit to the United States, Einstein knew he could not return to Germany with the rise to power of the Nazis under Germany's new chancellor, Adolf Hitler.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] While at American universities in early 1933, he undertook his third two-month visiting professorship at the California Institute of Technology in Pasadena.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] In February and March 1933, the Gestapo repeatedly raided his family's apartment in Berlin.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He and his wife Elsa returned to Europe in March, and during the trip, they learned that the German Reichstag had passed the Enabling Act on 23 March, transforming Hitler's government into a *de facto* legal dictatorship, and that they would not be able to proceed to Berlin.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Later on, they heard that their cottage had been raided by the Nazis and Einstein's personal sailboat confiscated.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Upon landing in Antwerp, Belgium on 28 March, Einstein immediately went to the German consulate and surrendered his passport, formally renouncing his German citizenship.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] The renunciation was at first refused, but the Nazi government finally revoked his citizenship on 24 March 1934.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] The Nazis later sold his boat and converted his cottage into a Hitler Youth camp.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] In April 1933, Einstein discovered that the new German government had passed laws barring Jews from holding any official positions, including teaching at universities.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Historian Gerald Holton describes how, with "virtually no audible protest being raised by their colleagues", thousands of Jewish scientists were suddenly forced to give up their university positions and their names were removed from the rolls of institutions where they were employed.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] In a subsequent letter to physicist and friend Max Born, who had already emigrated from Germany to England, Einstein wrote, "...
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was now without a permanent home, unsure where he would live and work, and equally worried about the fate of countless other scientists still in Germany.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Aided by the Academic Assistance Council, founded in April 1933 by British Liberal politician William Beveridge to help academics escape Nazi persecution, Einstein was able to leave Germany.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He rented a house in De Haan, Belgium, where he lived for a few months.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] In late July 1933, he visited England for about six weeks at the invitation of the British Member of Parliament Commander Oliver Locker-Lampson, who had become friends with him in the preceding years.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Locker-Lampson invited him to stay near his Cromer home in a secluded wooden cabin on Roughton Heath in the Parish of Roughton, Norfolk.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] To protect Einstein, Locker-Lampson had two bodyguards watch over him; a photo of them carrying shotguns and guarding Einstein was published in the *Daily Herald* on 24 July 1933.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Locker-Lampson took Einstein to meet Winston Churchill at his home, and later, Austen Chamberlain and former Prime Minister Lloyd George.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein asked them to help bring Jewish scientists out of Germany.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] British historian Martin Gilbert notes that Churchill responded immediately, and sent his friend physicist Frederick Lindemann to Germany to seek out Jewish scientists and place them in British universities.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Churchill later observed that as a result of Germany having driven the Jews out, they had lowered their "technical standards" and put the Allies' technology ahead of theirs.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein later contacted leaders of other nations, including Turkey's Prime Minister, İsmet İnönü, to whom he wrote in September 1933, requesting placement of unemployed German-Jewish scientists.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] As a result of Einstein's letter, Jewish invitees to Turkey eventually totaled over "1,000 saved individuals".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Locker-Lampson also submitted a bill to parliament to extend British citizenship to Einstein, during which period Einstein made a number of public appearances describing the crisis brewing in Europe.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] In one of his speeches he denounced Germany's treatment of Jews, while at the same time he introduced a bill promoting Jewish citizenship in Palestine, as they were being denied citizenship elsewhere.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] In his speech he described Einstein as a "citizen of the world" who should be offered a temporary shelter in the UK.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Both bills failed, however, and Einstein then accepted an earlier offer from the Institute for Advanced Study, in Princeton, New Jersey, US, to become a resident scholar.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] On 3 October 1933, Einstein delivered a speech on the importance of academic freedom before a packed audience at the Royal Albert Hall in London, with *The Times* reporting he was wildly cheered throughout.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Four days later he returned to the US and took up a position at the Institute for Advanced Study, noted for having become a refuge for scientists fleeing Nazi Germany.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] At the time, most American universities, including Harvard, Princeton and Yale, had minimal or no Jewish faculty or students, as a result of their Jewish quotas, which lasted until the late 1940s.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was still undecided about his future.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein's affiliation with the Institute for Advanced Study would last until his death in 1955.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He was one of the four first selected (along with John von Neumann, Kurt Gödel and Hermann Weyl) at the new Institute.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He soon developed a close friendship with Gödel; the two would take long walks together discussing their work.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Bruria Kaufman, his assistant, later became a physicist.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] During this period, Einstein tried to develop a unified field theory and to refute the accepted interpretation of quantum physics, both unsuccessfully.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He lived in Princeton at his home from 1935 onwards.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] The Albert Einstein House was made a National Historic Landmark in 1976.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] In 1939, a group of Hungarian scientists that included émigré physicist Leó Szilárd attempted to alert Washington, D.C. to ongoing Nazi atomic bomb research.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He was asked to lend his support by writing a letter, with Szilárd, to President Franklin D.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Roosevelt, recommending the US pay attention and engage in its own nuclear weapons research.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] The letter is believed to be "arguably the key stimulus for the U.S. adoption of serious investigations into nuclear weapons on the eve of the U.S. entry into World War II".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] In addition to the letter, Einstein used his connections with the Belgian royal family and the Belgian queen mother to get access with a personal envoy to the White House's Oval Office.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Some say that as a result of Einstein's letter and his meetings with Roosevelt, the US entered the "race" to develop the bomb, drawing on its "immense material, financial, and scientific resources" to initiate the Manhattan Project.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] For Einstein, "war was a disease ... [and] he called for resistance to war." By signing the letter to Roosevelt, some argue he went against his pacifist principles.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein became an American citizen in 1940.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Not long after settling into his career at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey, he expressed his appreciation of the meritocracy in American culture compared to Europe.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He recognized the "right of individuals to say and think what they pleased" without social barriers.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] As a result, individuals were encouraged, he said, to be more creative, a trait he valued from his early education.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein joined the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) in Princeton, where he campaigned for the civil rights of African Americans.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He considered racism America's "worst disease", seeing it as "handed down from one generation to the next".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] As part of his involvement, he corresponded with civil rights activist W.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Du Bois and was prepared to testify on his behalf during his trial as an alleged foreign agent in 1951.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] When Einstein offered to be a character witness for Du Bois, the judge decided to drop the case.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] In 1946, Einstein visited Lincoln University in Pennsylvania, a historically black college, where he was awarded an honorary degree.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Lincoln was the first university in the United States to grant college degrees to African Americans; alumni include Langston Hughes and Thurgood Marshall.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein gave a speech about racism in America, adding, "I do not intend to be quiet about it." A resident of Princeton recalls that Einstein had once paid the college tuition for a black student.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein has said, "Being a Jew myself, perhaps I can understand and empathize with how black people feel as victims of discrimination".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Isaacson writes that "When Marian Anderson, the black contralto, came to Princeton for a concert in 1937, the Nassau Inn refused her a room.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] So Einstein invited her to stay at his house on Main Street, in what was a deeply personal as well as symbolic gesture ...
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] In 1918, Einstein was one of the signatories of the founding proclamation of the German Democratic Party, a liberal party.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Later in his life, Einstein's political view was in favor of socialism and critical of capitalism, which he detailed in his essays such as "Why Socialism?".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] His opinions on the Bolsheviks also changed with time.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] In 1925, he criticized them for not having a "well-regulated system of government" and called their rule a "regime of terror and a tragedy in human history".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein offered and was called on to give judgments and opinions on matters often unrelated to theoretical physics or mathematics.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He strongly advocated the idea of a democratic global government that would check the power of nation-states in the framework of a world federation.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He wrote "I advocate world government because I am convinced that there is no other possible way of eliminating the most terrible danger in which man has ever found himself." The FBI created a secret dossier on Einstein in 1932; by the time of his death, it was 1,427 pages long.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was deeply impressed by Mahatma Gandhi, with whom he corresponded.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He described Gandhi as "a role model for the generations to come".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] The initial connection was established on 27 September 1931, when Wilfrid Israel took his Indian guest V.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Sundaram to his friend Einstein's summer home in the town of Caputh to meet him.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Sundaram was Gandhi's disciple and special envoy, whom Wilfrid Israel met while visiting India and visiting the Indian leader's home in 1925.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] During the visit, Einstein wrote a short letter to Gandhi that was delivered to him through Sundaram, and Gandhi responded quickly with his own letter.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Although in the end Einstein and Gandhi were unable to meet as they had hoped, the direct connection between them was established through Wilfrid Israel.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein, a Jew, was a figurehead leader in the establishment of the Hebrew University of Jerusalem, which opened in 1925.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Earlier, in 1921, he was asked by the biochemist and president of the World Zionist Organization, Chaim Weizmann, to help raise funds for the planned university.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He made suggestions for the creation of an Institute of Agriculture, a Chemical Institute and an Institute of Microbiology in order to fight the various ongoing epidemics such as malaria, which he called an "evil" that was undermining a third of the country's development.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He also promoted the establishment of an Oriental Studies Institute, to include language courses given in both Hebrew and Arabic.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was not a nationalist and opposed the creation of an independent Jewish state.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He felt that the waves of arriving Jews of the Aliyah could live alongside existing Arabs in Palestine.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] The state of Israel was established without his help in 1948; Einstein was limited to a marginal role in the Zionist movement.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Afterward, Einstein adopted a practical attitude, understanding that "there is no going back", and the new state must be supported.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Upon the death of Israeli president Weizmann in November 1952, Prime Minister David Ben-Gurion offered Einstein the largely ceremonial position of President of Israel at the urging of Ezriel Carlebach.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] The offer was presented by Israel's ambassador in Washington, Abba Eban, who explained that the offer "embodies the deepest respect which the Jewish people can repose in any of its sons".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein wrote that he was "deeply moved", but "at once saddened and ashamed" that he could not accept it.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein did not want the office, and the Israeli government did not want him to accept, but felt obliged to make the offer.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Yitzhak Navon, Ben-Gurion's political secretary, and later president, reports Ben-Gurion as saying "Tell me what to do if he says yes!
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] I've had to offer the post to him because it's impossible not to.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Per Lee Smolin, "I believe what allowed Einstein to achieve so much was primarily a moral quality.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He simply cared far more than most of his colleagues that the laws of physics have to explain everything in nature coherently and consistently." Einstein expounded his spiritual outlook in a wide array of writings and interviews.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He said he had sympathy for the impersonal pantheistic God of Baruch Spinoza's philosophy.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He did not believe in a personal god who concerns himself with fates and actions of human beings, a view which he described as naïve.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He clarified, however, that "I am not an atheist", preferring to call himself an agnostic, or a "deeply religious nonbeliever".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He wrote that "A spirit is manifest in the laws of the universe—a spirit vastly superior to that of man, and one in the face of which we with our modest powers must feel humble.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was primarily affiliated with non-religious humanist and Ethical Culture groups in both the UK and US.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He served on the advisory board of the First Humanist Society of New York, and was an honorary associate of the Rationalist Association, which publishes *New Humanist* in Britain.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] For the 75th anniversary of the New York Society for Ethical Culture, he stated that the idea of Ethical Culture embodied his personal conception of what is most valuable and enduring in religious idealism.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein had been sympathetic toward vegetarianism for a long time.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He became a vegetarian himself only during the last part of his life.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] In March 1954 he wrote in a letter: "So I am living without fats, without meat, without fish, but am feeling quite well this way.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein developed an appreciation for music at an early age.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] His mother played the piano reasonably well and wanted her son to learn the violin, not only to instill in him a love of music but also to help him assimilate into German culture.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] According to conductor Leon Botstein, Einstein began playing when he was 5.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] However, he did not enjoy it at that age.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] When he turned 13, he discovered Mozart's violin sonatas, whereupon he became enamored of Mozart's compositions and studied music more willingly.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein taught himself to play without "ever practicing systematically".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He said that "love is a better teacher than a sense of duty".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] At the age of 17, he was heard by a school examiner in Aarau while playing Beethoven's violin sonatas.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] The examiner stated afterward that his playing was "remarkable and revealing of 'great insight'".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] What struck the examiner, writes Botstein, was that Einstein "displayed a deep love of the music, a quality that was and remains in short supply.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Music took on a pivotal and permanent role in Einstein's life from that period on.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Although the idea of becoming a professional musician himself was not on his mind at any time, among those with whom Einstein played chamber music were a few professionals, including Kurt Appelbaum, and he performed for private audiences and friends.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Chamber music had also become a regular part of his social life while living in Bern, Zurich, and Berlin, where he played with Max Planck and his son, among others.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He is sometimes erroneously credited as the editor of the 1937 edition of the Köchel catalog of Mozart's work; that edition was prepared by Alfred Einstein, who may have been a distant relation.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] In 1931, while engaged in research at the California Institute of Technology, he visited the Zoellner family conservatory in Los Angeles, where he played some of Beethoven and Mozart's works with members of the Zoellner Quartet.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Near the end of his life, when the young Juilliard Quartet visited him in Princeton, he played his violin with them, and the quartet was "impressed by Einstein's level of coordination and intonation".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] On 17 April 1955, Einstein experienced internal bleeding caused by the rupture of an abdominal aortic aneurysm, which had previously been reinforced surgically by Rudolph Nissen in 1948.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] He took the draft of a speech he was preparing for a television appearance commemorating the state of Israel's seventh anniversary with him to the hospital, but he did not live to complete it.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein refused surgery, saying, "I want to go when I want.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] It is tasteless to prolong life artificially.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] I will do it elegantly." He died in the Princeton Hospital early the next morning at the age of 76, having continued to work until near the end.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] During the autopsy, the pathologist Thomas Stoltz Harvey removed Einstein's brain for preservation without the permission of his family, in the hope that the neuroscience of the future would be able to discover what made Einstein so intelligent.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein's remains were cremated in Trenton, New Jersey, and his ashes were scattered at an undisclosed location.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] In a memorial lecture delivered on 13 December 1965 at UNESCO headquarters, nuclear physicist J.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Robert Oppenheimer summarized his impression of Einstein as a person: "He was almost wholly without sophistication and wholly without worldliness ...
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein bequeathed his personal archives, library, and intellectual assets to the Hebrew University of Jerusalem in Israel.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Throughout his life, Einstein published hundreds of books and articles.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] He published more than 300 scientific papers and 150 non-scientific ones.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] On 5 December 2014, universities and archives announced the release of Einstein's papers, comprising more than 30,000 unique documents.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In addition to the work he did by himself, he also collaborated with other scientists on additional projects, including the Bose–Einstein statistics, the Einstein refrigerator and others.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's first paper, submitted in 1900 to *Annalen der Physik*, was on capillary attraction.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] It was published in 1901 with the title "Folgerungen aus den Capillaritätserscheinungen", which translates as "Conclusions from the capillarity phenomena".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Two papers he published in 1902–1903 (thermodynamics) attempted to interpret atomic phenomena from a statistical point of view.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] These papers were the foundation for the 1905 paper on Brownian motion, which showed that Brownian movement can be construed as firm evidence that molecules exist.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] His research in 1903 and 1904 was mainly concerned with the effect of finite atomic size on diffusion phenomena.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein returned to the problem of thermodynamic fluctuations, giving a treatment of the density variations in a fluid at its critical point.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Ordinarily, the density fluctuations are controlled by the second derivative of the free energy with respect to the density.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] At the critical point, this derivative is zero, leading to large fluctuations.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] The effect of density fluctuations is that light of all wavelengths is scattered, making the fluid look milky white.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein relates this to Rayleigh scattering, which is what happens when the fluctuation size is much smaller than the wavelength, and which explains why the sky is blue.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein quantitatively derived critical opalescence from a treatment of density fluctuations, and demonstrated how both the effect and Rayleigh scattering originate from the atomistic constitution of matter.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] The *Annus Mirabilis* papers are four articles pertaining to the photoelectric effect (which gave rise to quantum theory), Brownian motion, the special theory of relativity, and *E* = *mc*2 that Einstein published in the *Annalen der Physik* scientific journal in 1905.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] These four works contributed substantially to the foundation of modern physics and changed views on space, time, and matter.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's "*Zur Elektrodynamik bewegter Körper*" ("On the Electrodynamics of Moving Bodies") was received on 30 June 1905 and published 26 September of that same year.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] It reconciled conflicts between Maxwell's equations (the laws of electricity and magnetism) and the laws of Newtonian mechanics by introducing changes to the laws of mechanics.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Observationally, the effects of these changes are most apparent at high speeds (where objects are moving at speeds close to the speed of light).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] The theory developed in this paper later became known as Einstein's special theory of relativity.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] This paper predicted that, when measured in the frame of a relatively moving observer, a clock carried by a moving body would appear to slow down, and the body itself would contract in its direction of motion.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] This paper also argued that the idea of a luminiferous aether—one of the leading theoretical entities in physics at the time—was superfluous.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In his paper on mass–energy equivalence, Einstein produced *E* = *mc*2 as a consequence of his special relativity equations.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's 1905 work on relativity remained controversial for many years, but was accepted by leading physicists, starting with Max Planck.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein originally framed special relativity in terms of kinematics (the study of moving bodies).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In 1908, Hermann Minkowski reinterpreted special relativity in geometric terms as a theory of spacetime.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein adopted Minkowski's formalism in his 1915 general theory of relativity.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] General relativity (GR) is a theory of gravitation that was developed by Einstein between 1907 and 1915.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] According to it, the observed gravitational attraction between masses results from the warping of spacetime by those masses.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] General relativity has developed into an essential tool in modern astrophysics; it provides the foundation for the current understanding of black holes, regions of space where gravitational attraction is so strong that not even light can escape.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] As Einstein later said, the reason for the development of general relativity was that the preference of inertial motions within special relativity was unsatisfactory, while a theory which from the outset prefers no state of motion (even accelerated ones) should appear more satisfactory.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Consequently, in 1907 he published an article on acceleration under special relativity.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In that article titled "On the Relativity Principle and the Conclusions Drawn from It", he argued that free fall is really inertial motion, and that for a free-falling observer the rules of special relativity must apply.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] This argument is called the equivalence principle.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In the same article, Einstein also predicted the phenomena of gravitational time dilation, gravitational redshift and gravitational lensing.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In 1911, Einstein published another article "On the Influence of Gravitation on the Propagation of Light" expanding on the 1907 article, in which he estimated the amount of deflection of light by massive bodies.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Thus, the theoretical prediction of general relativity could for the first time be tested experimentally.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In 1916, Einstein predicted gravitational waves, ripples in the curvature of spacetime which propagate as waves, traveling outward from the source, transporting energy as gravitational radiation.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] The existence of gravitational waves is possible under general relativity due to its Lorentz invariance which brings the concept of a finite speed of propagation of the physical interactions of gravity with it.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] By contrast, gravitational waves cannot exist in the Newtonian theory of gravitation, which postulates that the physical interactions of gravity propagate at infinite speed.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] The first, indirect, detection of gravitational waves came in the 1970s through observation of a pair of closely orbiting neutron stars, PSR B1913+16.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] The explanation for the decay in their orbital period was that they were emitting gravitational waves.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's prediction was confirmed on 11 February 2016, when researchers at LIGO published the first observation of gravitational waves, detected on Earth on 14 September 2015, nearly one hundred years after the prediction.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] While developing general relativity, Einstein became confused about the gauge invariance in the theory.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] He formulated an argument that led him to conclude that a general relativistic field theory is impossible.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] He gave up looking for fully generally covariant tensor equations and searched for equations that would be invariant under general linear transformations only.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In June 1913, the Entwurf ('draft') theory was the result of these investigations.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] As its name suggests, it was a sketch of a theory, less elegant and more difficult than general relativity, with the equations of motion supplemented by additional gauge fixing conditions.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] After more than two years of intensive work, Einstein realized that the hole argument was mistaken and abandoned the theory in November 1915.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In 1917, Einstein applied the general theory of relativity to the structure of the universe as a whole.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] He discovered that the general field equations predicted a universe that was dynamic, either contracting or expanding.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] As observational evidence for a dynamic universe was lacking at the time, Einstein introduced a new term, the cosmological constant, into the field equations, in order to allow the theory to predict a static universe.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] The modified field equations predicted a static universe of closed curvature, in accordance with Einstein's understanding of Mach's principle in these years.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] This model became known as the Einstein World or Einstein's static universe.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] This paper is widely regarded as marking the emergence of modern theoretical cosmology.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Following the discovery of the recession of the galaxies by Edwin Hubble in 1929, Einstein abandoned his static model of the universe, and proposed two dynamic models of the cosmos, the Friedmann–Einstein universe of 1931 and the Einstein–de Sitter universe of 1932.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In each of these models, Einstein discarded the cosmological constant, claiming that it was "in any case theoretically unsatisfactory".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In many Einstein biographies, it is claimed that Einstein referred to the cosmological constant in later years as his "biggest blunder", based on a letter George Gamow claimed to have received from him.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] The astrophysicist Mario Livio has cast doubt on this claim.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In late 2013, a team led by the Irish physicist Cormac O'Raifeartaigh discovered evidence that, shortly after learning of Hubble's observations of the recession of the galaxies, Einstein considered a steady-state model of the universe.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In a hitherto overlooked manuscript, apparently written in early 1931, Einstein explored a model of the expanding universe in which the density of matter remains constant due to a continuous creation of matter, a process that he associated with the cosmological constant.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] It thus appears that Einstein considered a steady-state model of the expanding universe many years before Hoyle, Bondi and Gold.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] However, Einstein's steady-state model contained a fundamental flaw and he quickly abandoned the idea.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] General relativity includes a dynamical spacetime, so it is difficult to see how to identify the conserved energy and momentum.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Noether's theorem allows these quantities to be determined from a Lagrangian with translation invariance, but general covariance makes translation invariance into something of a gauge symmetry.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] The energy and momentum derived within general relativity by Noether's prescriptions do not make a real tensor for this reason.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein argued that this is true for a fundamental reason: the gravitational field could be made to vanish by a choice of coordinates.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] He maintained that the non-covariant energy momentum pseudotensor was, in fact, the best description of the energy momentum distribution in a gravitational field.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] While the use of non-covariant objects like pseudotensors was criticized by Erwin Schrödinger and others, Einstein's approach has been echoed by physicists including Lev Landau and Evgeny Lifshitz.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In 1935, Einstein collaborated with Nathan Rosen to produce a model of a wormhole, often called Einstein–Rosen bridges.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] His motivation was to model elementary particles with charge as a solution of gravitational field equations, in line with the program outlined in the paper "Do Gravitational Fields play an Important Role in the Constitution of the Elementary Particles?".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] These solutions cut and pasted Schwarzschild black holes to make a bridge between two patches.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Because these solutions included spacetime curvature without the presence of a physical body, Einstein and Rosen suggested that they could provide the beginnings of a theory that avoided the notion of point particles.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] However, it was later found that Einstein–Rosen bridges are not stable.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In order to incorporate spinning point particles into general relativity, the affine connection needed to be generalized to include an antisymmetric part, called the torsion.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] This modification was made by Einstein and Cartan in the 1920s.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In general relativity, gravitational force is reimagined as curvature of spacetime.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] A curved path like an orbit is not the result of a force deflecting a body from an ideal straight-line path, but rather the body's attempt to fall freely through a background that is itself curved by the presence of other masses.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] The geodesic equation covers the former aspect, stating that freely falling bodies follow lines that are as straight as possible in a curved spacetime.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein regarded this as an "independent fundamental assumption" that had to be postulated in addition to the field equations in order to complete the theory.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Believing this to be a shortcoming in how general relativity was originally presented, he wished to derive it from the field equations themselves.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Since the equations of general relativity are non-linear, a lump of energy made out of pure gravitational fields, like a black hole, would move on a trajectory which is determined by the Einstein field equations themselves, not by a new law.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Accordingly, Einstein proposed that the field equations would determine the path of a singular solution, like a black hole, to be a geodesic.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Both physicists and philosophers have often repeated the assertion that the geodesic equation can be obtained from applying the field equations to the motion of a gravitational singularity, but this claim remains disputed.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In a 1905 paper, Einstein postulated that light itself consists of localized particles (*quanta*).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's light quanta were nearly universally rejected by all physicists, including Max Planck and Niels Bohr.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] This idea only became universally accepted in 1919, with Robert Millikan's detailed experiments on the photoelectric effect, and with the measurement of Compton scattering.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein concluded that each wave of frequency *f* is associated with a collection of photons with energy *hf* each, where *h* is the Planck constant.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] He did not say much more, because he was not sure how the particles were related to the wave.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] But he did suggest that this idea would explain certain experimental results, notably the photoelectric effect.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Light quanta were dubbed *photons* by Gilbert N.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In 1907, Einstein proposed a model of matter where each atom in a lattice structure is an independent harmonic oscillator.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In the Einstein model, each atom oscillates independently—a series of equally spaced quantized states for each oscillator.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein was aware that getting the frequency of the actual oscillations would be difficult, but he nevertheless proposed this theory because it was a particularly clear demonstration that quantum mechanics could solve the specific heat problem in classical mechanics.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In 1924, Einstein received a description of a statistical model from Indian physicist Satyendra Nath Bose, based on a counting method that assumed that light could be understood as a gas of indistinguishable particles.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein noted that Bose's statistics applied to some atoms as well as to the proposed light particles, and submitted his translation of Bose's paper to the *Zeitschrift für Physik*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein also published his own articles describing the model and its implications, among them the Bose–Einstein condensate phenomenon that some particulates should appear at very low temperatures.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] It was not until 1995 that the first such condensate was produced experimentally by Eric Allin Cornell and Carl Wieman using ultra-cooling equipment built at the NIST–JILA laboratory at the University of Colorado at Boulder.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Bose–Einstein statistics are now used to describe the behaviors of any assembly of bosons.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's sketches for this project may be seen in the Einstein Archive in the library of the Leiden University.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Although the patent office promoted Einstein to Technical Examiner Second Class in 1906, he had not given up on academia.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In 1908, he became a *Privatdozent* at the University of Bern.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] This paper introduced the *photon* concept and inspired the notion of wave–particle duality in quantum mechanics.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein saw this wave–particle duality in radiation as concrete evidence for his conviction that physics needed a new, unified foundation.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In a series of works completed from 1911 to 1913, Planck reformulated his 1900 quantum theory and introduced the idea of zero-point energy in his "second quantum theory".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Soon, this idea attracted the attention of Einstein and his assistant Otto Stern.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Assuming the energy of rotating diatomic molecules contains zero-point energy, they then compared the theoretical specific heat of hydrogen gas with the experimental data.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] However, after publishing the findings, they promptly withdrew their support, because they no longer had confidence in the correctness of the idea of zero-point energy.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In 1917, at the height of his work on relativity, Einstein published an article in *Physikalische Zeitschrift* that proposed the possibility of stimulated emission, the physical process that makes possible the maser and the laser.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] This article showed that the statistics of absorption and emission of light would only be consistent with Planck's distribution law if the emission of light into a mode with n photons would be enhanced statistically compared to the emission of light into an empty mode.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] This paper was enormously influential in the later development of quantum mechanics, because it was the first paper to show that the statistics of atomic transitions had simple laws.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein discovered Louis de Broglie's work and supported his ideas, which were received skeptically at first.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In another major paper from this era, Einstein observed that de Broglie waves could explain the quantization rules of Bohr and Sommerfeld.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] This paper would inspire Schrödinger's work of 1926.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein played a major role in developing quantum theory, beginning with his 1905 paper on the photoelectric effect.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] However, he became displeased with modern quantum mechanics as it had evolved after 1925, despite its acceptance by other physicists.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] He was skeptical that the randomness of quantum mechanics was fundamental rather than the result of determinism, stating that God "is not playing at dice".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Until the end of his life, he continued to maintain that quantum mechanics was incomplete.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] The Bohr–Einstein debates were a series of public disputes about quantum mechanics between Einstein and Niels Bohr, who were two of its founders.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Their debates are remembered because of their importance to the philosophy of science.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Their debates would influence later interpretations of quantum mechanics.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein never fully accepted quantum mechanics.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] While he recognized that it made correct predictions, he believed a more fundamental description of nature must be possible.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Over the years he presented multiple arguments to this effect, but the one he preferred most dated to a debate with Bohr in 1930.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein suggested a thought experiment in which two objects are allowed to interact and then moved apart a great distance from each other.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] The quantum-mechanical description of the two objects is a mathematical entity known as a wavefunction.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] If the wavefunction that describes the two objects before their interaction is given, then the Schrödinger equation provides the wavefunction that describes them after their interaction.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] But because of what would later be called quantum entanglement, measuring one object would lead to an instantaneous change of the wavefunction describing the other object, no matter how far away it is.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Moreover, the choice of which measurement to perform upon the first object would affect what wavefunction could result for the second object.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein reasoned that no influence could propagate from the first object to the second instantaneously fast.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Indeed, he argued, physics depends on being able to tell one thing apart from another, and such instantaneous influences would call that into question.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Because the true "physical condition" of the second object could not be immediately altered by an action done to the first, Einstein concluded, the wavefunction could not be that true physical condition, only an incomplete description of it.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] A more famous version of this argument came in 1935, when Einstein published a paper with Boris Podolsky and Nathan Rosen that laid out what would become known as the EPR paradox.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In this thought experiment, two particles interact in such a way that the wavefunction describing them is entangled.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Then, no matter how far the two particles were separated, a precise position measurement on one particle would imply the ability to predict, perfectly, the result of measuring the position of the other particle.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Likewise, a precise momentum measurement of one particle would result in an equally precise prediction for of the momentum of the other particle, without needing to disturb the other particle in any way.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] They argued that no action taken on the first particle could instantaneously affect the other, since this would involve information being transmitted faster than light, which is forbidden by the theory of relativity.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] But quantum mechanics considers these two observables incompatible and thus does not associate simultaneous values for both to any system.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein, Podolsky, and Rosen therefore concluded that quantum theory does not provide a complete description of reality.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In 1964, John Stewart Bell carried the analysis of quantum entanglement much further.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] He deduced that if measurements are performed independently on the two separated particles of an entangled pair, then the assumption that the outcomes depend upon hidden variables within each half implies a mathematical constraint on how the outcomes on the two measurements are correlated.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] This constraint would later be called a Bell inequality.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Bell then showed that quantum physics predicts correlations that violate this inequality.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Consequently, the only way that hidden variables could explain the predictions of quantum physics is if they are "nonlocal", which is to say that somehow the two particles are able to interact instantaneously no matter how widely they ever become separated.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Bell argued that because an explanation of quantum phenomena in terms of hidden variables would require nonlocality, the EPR paradox "is resolved in the way which Einstein would have liked least".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Despite this, and although Einstein personally found the argument in the EPR paper overly complicated, that paper became among the most influential papers published in *Physical Review*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] It is considered a centerpiece of the development of quantum information theory.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Encouraged by his success with general relativity, Einstein sought an even more ambitious geometrical theory that would treat gravitation and electromagnetism as aspects of a single entity.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In 1950, he described his unified field theory in a *Scientific American* article titled "On the Generalized Theory of Gravitation".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] His attempt to find the most fundamental laws of nature won him praise but not success: a particularly conspicuous blemish of his model was that it did not accommodate the strong and weak nuclear forces, neither of which was well understood until many years after his death.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Although most researchers now believe that Einstein's approach to unifying physics was mistaken, his goal of a theory of everything is one to which his successors still aspire.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein conducted other investigations that were unsuccessful and abandoned.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] These pertain to force, superconductivity, and other research.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In addition to longtime collaborators Leopold Infeld, Nathan Rosen, Peter Bergmann and others, Einstein also had some one-shot collaborations with various scientists.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In 1908, Owen Willans Richardson predicted that a change in the magnetic moment of a free body will cause this body to rotate.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] This effect is a consequence of the conservation of angular momentum and is strong enough to be observable in ferromagnetic materials.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein and Wander Johannes de Haas published two papers in 1915 claiming the first experimental observation of the effect.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Measurements of this kind demonstrate that the phenomenon of magnetization is caused by the alignment (polarization) of the angular momenta of the electrons in the material along the axis of magnetization.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] These measurements also allow the separation of the two contributions to the magnetization: that which is associated with the spin and with the orbital motion of the electrons.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] The Einstein-de Haas experiment is the only experiment conceived, realized and published by Albert Einstein himself.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] A complete original version of the Einstein-de Haas experimental equipment was donated by Geertruida de Haas-Lorentz, wife of de Haas and daughter of Lorentz, to the Ampère Museum in Lyon France in 1961 where it is currently on display.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] It was lost among the museum's holdings and was rediscovered in 2023.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In 1926, Einstein and his former student Leó Szilárd co-invented (and in 1930, patented) the Einstein refrigerator.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] This absorption refrigerator was then revolutionary for having no moving parts and using only heat as an input.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] On 11 November 1930, U.S. patent 1,781,541 was awarded to Einstein and Leó Szilárd for the refrigerator.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Their invention was not immediately put into commercial production, but the most promising of their patents were acquired by the Swedish company Electrolux.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein also invented an electromagnetic pump, sound reproduction device, and several other household devices.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] While traveling, Einstein wrote daily to his wife Elsa and adopted stepdaughters Margot and Ilse.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] The letters were included in the papers bequeathed to the Hebrew University of Jerusalem.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Margot Einstein permitted the personal letters to be made available to the public, but requested that it not be done until twenty years after her death (she died in 1986).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Barbara Wolff, of the Hebrew University's Albert Einstein Archives, told the BBC that there are about 3,500 pages of private correspondence written between 1912 and 1955.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In his final four years, Einstein was involved with the establishment of the Albert Einstein College of Medicine in New York City.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In 1979, the Albert Einstein Memorial was unveiled outside the National Academy of Sciences building in Washington, D.C. for the Einstein centenary.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein can be seen holding a paper with three of his most important equations: for the photoelectric effect, general relativity and mass-energy equivalence.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's right of publicity was litigated in 2015 in a federal district court in California.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Although the court initially held that the right had expired, that ruling was immediately appealed, and the decision was later vacated in its entirety.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] The underlying claims between the parties in that lawsuit were ultimately settled.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] The right is enforceable, and the Hebrew University of Jerusalem is the exclusive representative of that right.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Corbis, successor to The Roger Richman Agency, licenses the use of his name and associated imagery, as agent for the university.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Mount Einstein in the Chugach Mountains of Alaska was named in 1955.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Mount Einstein in New Zealand's Paparoa Range was named after him in 1970 by the Department of Scientific and Industrial Research.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In 1999, Einstein was named *Time*'s Person of the Century.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In 1999, a survey of the top 100 physicists voted for Einstein as the "greatest physicist ever", while a parallel survey of rank-and-file physicists gave the top spot to Isaac Newton, with Einstein second.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Simmons ranked Einstein second after Newton in *The Scientific 100*, based on a qualitative assessment in which he ordered the scientists according to overall influence, and noted that the work of Einstein "forms the source of twentieth-century physics".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] The International Union of Pure and Applied Physics declared 2005 the "World Year of Physics", also known as "Einstein Year", in recognition of Einstein's "miracle year" in 1905.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] It was also declared the "International Year of Physics" by the United Nations.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein became one of the most famous scientific celebrities after the confirmation of his general theory of relativity in 1919.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Although most of the public had little understanding of his work, he was widely recognized and admired.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] In the period before World War II, *The New Yorker* published a vignette in their "The Talk of the Town" feature saying that Einstein was so well known in America that he would be stopped on the street by people wanting him to explain "that theory".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Eventually he came to cope with unwanted enquirers by pretending to be someone else: "Pardon me, sorry!
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein has been the subject of or inspiration for many novels, films, plays, and works of music.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] He is a favorite model for depictions of absent-minded professors; his expressive face and distinctive hairstyle have been widely copied and exaggerated.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] *Time* magazine's Frederic Golden wrote that Einstein was "a cartoonist's dream come true".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] His intellectual achievements and originality made *Einstein* broadly synonymous with *genius*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Many popular quotations are often misattributed to him.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein received numerous awards and honors, and in 1922, he was awarded the 1921 Nobel Prize in Physics "for his services to Theoretical Physics, and especially for his discovery of the law of the photoelectric effect".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] The Nobel committee decided that none of the nominations in 1921 met the criteria set by Alfred Nobel, so the 1921 prize was carried forward and awarded to Einstein in 1922.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] Einsteinium, a synthetic chemical element, was named in his honor in 1955, a few months after his death.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] (Public Domain) *Einstein, Albert (1926).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/albert-einstein-p04] London & New York: The Encyclopædia Britannica Company. pp.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness began his stage career in 1934.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Two years later, at the age of 22, he played the role of Osric in *Hamlet* in the West End and joined the Old Vic.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] He continued to play Shakespearean roles throughout his career.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] He served in the Royal Naval Reserve during the Second World War and commanded a landing craft during the invasion of Sicily and Elba.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] He went on to lead roles in 1951 with *The Man in the White Suit* and *The Lavender Hill Mob* (for which he received his first Academy Award nomination for Best Actor), then in 1955 with *The Ladykillers*, and culminating in 1957 with *Barnacle Bill*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness collaborated six times with director David Lean: as Herbert Pocket in *Great Expectations* (1946); Fagin in *Oliver Twist* (1948); Col.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Nicholson in *The Bridge on the River Kwai* (1957), for which he won both the Academy Award and the BAFTA Award for Best Actor; Prince Faisal in *Lawrence of Arabia* (1962); General Yevgraf Zhivago in *Doctor Zhivago* (1965); and Professor Godbole in *A Passage to India* (1984).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] In 1970, Guinness played Jacob Marley's ghost in Ronald Neame's *Scrooge*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] He also portrayed Obi-Wan Kenobi in George Lucas's original *Star Wars* trilogy, which brought him further recognition; for his performance in the original 1977 film, he was nominated as Best Supporting Actor for the Academy Award and Golden Globe.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness's later life was closely associated with his definitive depiction of the leading role of George Smiley in the BBC television series *Tinker, Tailor, Soldier, Spy* and *Smiley's People* by John le Carré.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness was born Alec Guinness de Cuffe at 155 Lauderdale Mansions South, Lauderdale Road, in Maida Vale, London.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] His mother's maiden name was Agnes Cuff; she was born on 8 December 1890 to Edward Charles Cuff, a sometime lifeguard at Bournemouth who had served in the Royal Navy, and Mary Ann, née Benfield, of a family of stonemasons and publicans.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] On Guinness's birth certificate, his mother's name is given as Agnes de Cuffe; the infant's name (where first names only are placed) is given as Alec Guinness, and there are no details for the father.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] The identity of Guinness's father has never been officially confirmed.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Agnes Cuff had worked at Cowes on the Isle of Wight as a barmaid at the Royal Yacht Squadron clubhouse at the time of the Cowes Regatta in 1913, which was attended by several members of the Guinness family including Edward Guinness, 1st Earl of Iveagh, and his sons Ernest and Walter.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] From 1875, under English law, when the birth of an illegitimate child was registered, the father's name could be entered on the certificate only if he was present and gave his consent.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness himself believed that his father was a Scottish banker, Andrew Geddes (1861–1928), who paid for Guinness's boarding-school education at Pembroke Lodge, in Southbourne, and Roborough, in Eastbourne.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Geddes—who with a "round face and sticking-out ears" bore a resemblance to Guinness and believed himself to be his father—occasionally visited Guinness and his mother, posing as an uncle.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness's mother later had a three-year marriage to a Scottish army captain named Stiven, whose behaviour was often erratic or even violent.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness first worked writing advertising copy.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] He appeared at the New Theatre in 1936 at the age of 22, playing the role of Osric in John Gielgud's successful production of *Hamlet*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Also in 1936, Guinness signed on with the Old Vic, where he was cast in a series of classic roles.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] In the later 1930s, he took classes at the London Theatre Studio.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] In 1939, he took over for Michael Redgrave as Charleston in a road-show production of Robert Ardrey's *Thunder Rock*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] At the Old Vic, Guinness worked with many actors and actresses who became his friends and frequent co-stars in the future, including Gielgud, Ralph Richardson, Peggy Ashcroft, Anthony Quayle, and Jack Hawkins.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] An early influence was film star Stan Laurel, whom Guinness admired.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness continued playing Shakespearean roles throughout his career.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] In 1937, he played Aumerle in *Richard II* and Lorenzo in *The Merchant of Venice* under the direction of John Gielgud.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] He starred in a 1938 production of *Hamlet* which won him acclaim on both sides of the Atlantic.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] He also appeared as Romeo in a production of *Romeo and Juliet* (1939), Malvolio in *Twelfth Night*, and as Exeter in *Henry V* in 1937, both opposite Laurence Olivier, and Ferdinand in *The Tempest*, opposite Gielgud as Prospero.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] In 1939, he adapted Charles Dickens's novel *Great Expectations* for the stage, playing Herbert Pocket.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] One of its viewers was a young British film editor, David Lean, who later had Guinness reprise his role in Lean's 1946 film adaptation of the novel.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness served in the Royal Navy Volunteer Reserve in the Second World War, initially as a seaman in 1941, before receiving a commission as a temporary Sub-lieutenant on 30 April 1942 and a promotion to Temporary Lieutenant the following year.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness then commanded a Landing Craft Infantry at the Allied invasion of Sicily, and later ferried supplies and agents to the Yugoslav partisans in the eastern Mediterranean theatre.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] During the war, Guinness was granted leave to appear in the Broadway production of Terence Rattigan's stage play *Flare Path*, about RAF Bomber Command, with Guinness playing the role of Flight Lieutenant Teddy Graham.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] After leaving the Old Vic, he played Eric Birling in J.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Priestley's *An Inspector Calls* at the New Theatre in October 1946.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] He played the Uninvited Guest in the Broadway production of T.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Eliot's *The Cocktail Party* (1950, revived at the Edinburgh Festival in 1968).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] He played *Hamlet* under his own direction at the New Theatre in the West End in 1951.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Invited by his friend Tyrone Guthrie to join the premiere season of the Stratford Festival of Canada, Guinness lived for a brief time in Stratford, Ontario.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness won a Tony Award for Best Lead Actor in a Play for his Broadway performance as Welsh poet Dylan Thomas in *Dylan*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] He next played the title role in *Macbeth* opposite Simone Signoret at the Royal Court Theatre in 1966.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness made his final stage performance at the Comedy Theatre in the West End on 30 May 1989, in the play *A Walk in the Woods*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] In all, between 2 April 1934 and 30 May 1989, he played 77 parts in the theatre.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness made his speaking debut in film in the drama *Great Expectations* (1946).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] He was initially mainly associated with the Ealing comedies, and particularly for playing eight characters in *Kind Hearts and Coronets* (1949).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] His other films from this period included *Oliver Twist* (1948), *The Lavender Hill Mob*, *The Man in the White Suit* (both 1951) and *The Ladykillers* (1955), with all four, as well as *Great Expectations and* *Kind Hearts and Coronets,* ranked among the Best British films.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] In 1950, he portrayed 19th-century British prime minister Benjamin Disraeli in *The Mudlark*, which included delivering an uninterrupted seven-minute speech in Parliament.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] In 1952, director Ronald Neame cast Guinness in his first romantic lead role, opposite Petula Clark in *The Card*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] In 1951, a poll of British exhibitors identified Guinness as the top box office attraction in British films and fifth in international films, based on box office returns.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness was idolised by Peter Sellers—who himself became famous for inhabiting a variety of characters in a film—with Sellers's first major film role starring alongside his idol in *The Ladykillers*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Another role that is sometimes referred to as one he considered his best, and is also considered so by many critics, is that of Major Jock Sinclair in *Tunes of Glory* (1960).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness also played the role of Jamessir Bensonmum, the blind butler, in the 1976 Neil Simon film *Murder by Death*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness won particular praise for his collaborations with director David Lean, which today represent his most critically acclaimed work.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] After appearing in Lean's *Great Expectations* and *Oliver Twist*, he was given a starring role opposite William Holden in *The Bridge on the River Kwai*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] For his performance as Colonel Nicholson, the unyielding British POW commanding officer, Guinness won both the Academy Award for Best Actor and BAFTA Award for Best Actor.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] He was also offered a role in Lean's *Ryan's Daughter* (1970) but declined.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] At that time, Guinness "mistrusted" Lean and considered the formerly close relationship to be strained—although he recalled, at Lean's funeral, that the famed director had been "charming and affable".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness appeared in five Lean films that were ranked in the British Film Institute's 50 greatest British films of the 20th century: 3rd (*Lawrence of Arabia*), 5th (*Great Expectations*), 11th (*The Bridge on the River Kwai*), 27th (*Doctor Zhivago*) and 46th (*Oliver Twist*).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness's role as Obi-Wan Kenobi in the original *Star Wars* trilogy, beginning in 1977 with *Star Wars*, brought him worldwide recognition to a new generation, as well as Academy Award and Golden Globe nominations.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] In letters to his friends, Guinness described the film as "fairy-tale rubbish" but the film's sense of moral good—and the studio's doubling of his initial salary offer—appealed to him.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] He agreed to take the part of Kenobi on the condition that he would not have to do any publicity to promote the film.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] He initially negotiated a deal for 2% of the film's royalties paid to the director, George Lucas.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Upon the warm reception of the film with the press and film critics, and as a gesture of good-will for the positive amendments and suggestions Guinness proposed to the screenplay for the film, Lucas offered Guinness an additional 0.5%, bringing his share to 2.5%.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Upon his first viewing of the film, Guinness wrote in his diary, "It's a pretty staggering film as spectacle and technically brilliant.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness soon became unhappy with being identified with the part and expressed dismay at the fan following that the *Star Wars* trilogy attracted.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] In the DVD commentary of the original *Star Wars*, Lucas says that Guinness was not happy with the script rewrite in which Obi-Wan is killed.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness said in a 1999 interview that it was actually his idea to kill off Obi-Wan, persuading Lucas that it would make him a stronger character and that Lucas agreed to the idea.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness stated in the interview, "What I didn't tell Lucas was that I just couldn't go on speaking those bloody awful, banal lines.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] I'd had enough of the mumbo jumbo." He went on to say that he "shrivelled up" every time *Star Wars* was mentioned to him.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Although Guinness disliked the fame that followed and he did not hold the work in high esteem, Lucas and fellow cast members Mark Hamill, Harrison Ford, Carrie Fisher, Kenny Baker, and Anthony Daniels have spoken highly of his courtesy and professionalism, on and off the set.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Lucas credited him with inspiring the cast and crew to work harder, saying that Guinness contributed significantly to achieving completion of the filming.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness appeared in the film's sequels *The Empire Strikes Back* (1980) and *Return of the Jedi* (1983), as a force ghost apparition to the trilogy's main character Luke Skywalker.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] In 2003, Obi-Wan Kenobi as portrayed by Guinness was selected as the 37th-greatest hero in cinema history by the American Film Institute.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Digitally altered archival audio of Guinness's voice was used in the films *Star Wars: The Force Awakens* (2015) and *Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker* (2019).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness was reluctant to appear on television, but accepted the part of George Smiley in the BBC Television serialisation of John le Carré's *Tinker Tailor Soldier Spy* (1979) after meeting the author.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness reprised the role in *Smiley's People* (1982), and twice won the British Academy Television Award for Best Actor for his portrayal of the character.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] He received another nomination for best actor for his role in *Monsignor Quixote* in 1987.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] One of Guinness's last appearances was in the BBC drama *Eskimo Day* (1996).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness received an Academy Honorary Award for lifetime achievement in 1980.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] In 1985 the Hamburg-based Alfred Toepfer Foundation awarded Guinness its annual Shakespeare Prize in recognition of his life's work.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] He received the BAFTA Academy Fellowship Award for lifetime achievement in 1989.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] For his theatre work, Guinness received an Evening Standard Award for his performance as T.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Lawrence in *Ross* and a Tony Award for his Broadway turn as Dylan Thomas in *Dylan*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] He received a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame at 1559 Vine Street on 8 February 1960.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness was appointed a Commander of the Order of the British Empire (CBE) in the 1955 Birthday Honours, was knighted by Elizabeth II in the 1959 New Year Honours, and was made a Member of the Order of the Companions of Honour in the 1994 Birthday Honours for services to drama.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] In 1991, he received an honorary doctorate from Cambridge University.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] In 2014, Guinness was among the ten people commemorated on a UK postage stamp issued by the Royal Mail in their "Remarkable Lives" issue.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness married the artist, playwright and actress Merula Silvia Salaman (1914–2000) in 1938; in 1940, they had a son, Matthew Guinness, who later became an actor.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] From the 1950s the family lived at Kettlebrook Meadows, near Steep Marsh in Hampshire.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] The house itself was designed by Merula's brother Eusty Salaman.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] His great-grandson Nesta Guinness-Walker is a professional footballer.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] A biography claimed that Guinness was arrested, charged and fined for a homosexual act in a public lavatory in Liverpool in 1946.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Piers Paul Read, who wrote his authorised biography, did not believe it happened.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Another biography suggests: "The rumour is possibly a conflation of stories about Alec's 'cottaging' and the arrest of John Gielgud, in October 1953, in a public lavatory in Chelsea, after dining with the Guinnesses at St.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] While serving in the Royal Navy, Guinness had planned to become an Anglican priest.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] In 1954, while he was filming *Father Brown* in Burgundy, Guinness, who was in costume as a Catholic priest, was mistaken for a real priest by a local child.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness was far from fluent in French, and the child apparently did not notice that Guinness did not understand him but took his hand and chatted while the two strolled; the child then waved and trotted off.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] The confidence and affection the clerical attire appeared to inspire in the boy left a deep impression on the actor.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] When their son was ill with polio at the age of 11, Guinness began visiting a church to pray.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] A few years later, in 1956, Guinness converted to the Catholic Church.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] His wife, who was of paternal Sephardi Jewish descent, followed suit in 1957 while he was in Ceylon filming *The Bridge on the River Kwai*, and she informed him only after the event.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness told a story in a media interview and wrote in his memoir that he met James Dean and predicted Dean's death one week before he was killed in a car accident in 1955.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] In interviews shortly after Dean's death, Guinness recalled that all of Dean's friends had issued similar warnings because he drove too fast.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Every morning, Guinness recited verse eight from Psalm 143, "Cause me to hear your loving kindness in the morning".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness died on the night of 5 August 2000 at King Edward VII's Hospital in Midhurst, West Sussex.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] He had been diagnosed with prostate cancer in February 2000, and with liver cancer two days before he died.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] His wife, who died two months later on 18 October 2000, also had liver cancer.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Laurence Catholic Church in Petersfield, Hampshire, and he was interred at Petersfield Cemetery.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] In 2013 the British Library acquired the personal archive of Guinness consisting of over 900 letters, manuscripts for plays, and 100 volumes of diaries from the late 1930s to his death.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] For a number of years, British film exhibitors voted Guinness among the most popular stars in Britain at the box office via an annual poll in the *Motion Picture Herald*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Guinness wrote three volumes of a best-selling autobiography, beginning with *Blessings in Disguise* in 1985, followed by *My Name Escapes Me* in 1996, and *A Positively Final Appearance* in 1999.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] He recorded each of them as an audiobook.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Shortly after his death, Lady Guinness asked the couple's close friend and fellow Catholic, novelist Piers Paul Read, to write Guinness's official biography.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] On 19 September 2025, it was announced Zeb Soanes would return to the stage to play Guinness, his hero, in a one-man-show, touring the UK in 2026.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] Soanes wrote to Guinness when he was aged 17 and received a handwritten note of encouragement.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] *Two Halves of Guinness*, by Mark Burgess, follows Guinness as he reflects on his distinguished but mysterious life and career, including his fears that he would only be remembered for the iconic role of the Jedi Knight Obi-Wan Kenobi in *Star Wars*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alec-guinness] The play, directed by Selina Cadell, opened at the Watermill Theatre, Newbury on 29 January 2026 and transferred to the Park Theatre, London on 20 April.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] Agassiz was born in Neuchâtel, Switzerland, and immigrated to the United States in 1849, joining his father Louis Agassiz, after his mother Cecile (Braun) Agassiz died in 1848.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] Thereupon, his father enrolled him in the Cambridge High School, before entering Harvard at the age of 15.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] He graduated from Harvard University in 1855, subsequently studying engineering and chemistry, and taking the degree of Bachelor of Science at the Lawrence Scientific School of the same institution in 1857; in 1859 became an assistant in the United States Coast Survey, onboard the Fauntleroy.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] In 1860, he became an agent for the Museum of Comparative Zoology, and married Anna Russell.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] Thenceforward he became a specialist in marine ichthyology.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] Agassiz was elected a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1862.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] Up until the summer of 1866, Agassiz worked as assistant curator in the museum of natural history that his father founded at Harvard.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] Hulbert persuaded Agassiz's brother-in-law, Quincy Adams Shaw, and friends to invest in a rich copper lode discovered on Michigan's Keweenaw Peninsula, called the Calumet Mine.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] In 1866, Agassiz visited the outcrop and noted that the Calumet Conglomerate was a porphyry almost fourteen feet wide, dipping to the northwest at a 35 degree angle.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] The rich nature of the deposit convinced Shaw to purchase the land to the south, forming the Hecla Mining Company.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] Agassiz was then made treasurer of both companies.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] Disappointed in Hulbert's management of the Calumet, Agassiz replaced Hulbert with a new manager called Davis in December.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] Agassiz states, "I have put in every cent of mine into these two mines." Convinced the deposit could be developed at a profit, Agassiz was made superintendent of both mines, and arrived on site in March 1867.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] By September 1868, Hecla was producing 185 tons of ingot, the Calumet 140, and both mills stamping 4000 tons of rock per month.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] Agassiz was able to place George Hardie in charge, and returned to Cambridge in October.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] Agassiz continued to visit the mines every spring and fall.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] In December 1869, the Hecla paid its first dividend, and the Calumet did so in August 1870.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] In May 1871, the Calumet and Hecla Mining Company was formed after consolidating with the Portland and Scott Mining Companies.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] Shaw was the first president, but soon retired to the board of directors, when Agassiz assumed the presidency until his death.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] In 1883, Agassiz innovated by installing a giant engine, known as the Superior, which was able to lift 24 tons of rock from a depth of 1,200 metres (3,900 feet).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] He also built a railroad and dredged a channel to navigable waters.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] With Erasmus Darwin Leavitt Jr. employed as his mechanical engineer, Agassiz installed state of the art hoisting engines.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] Out of his copper fortune, he gave some US$500,000 to Harvard for the museum of comparative zoology and other purposes.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] In 1875, Agassiz built a marine laboratory on his summer estate located at Castle Hill, Newport, Rhode Island, hoping to carry on the work his father started at Penikese Island.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] In 1877, Agassiz opened the Newport Marine Zoological Laboratory.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] Agassiz hosted grad students there until 1897, and continued to use the lab until his death.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] He assisted Charles Wyville Thomson in the examination and classification of the collections of the 1872 *Challenger* Expedition, and wrote the *Review of the Echini* (2 vols., 1872–1874) in the reports.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] Between 1877 and 1880, he took part in the three dredging expeditions of the steamer *Blake* of the Coast Survey (renamed the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey in 1878), and presented a full account of them in two volumes (1888).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] Also in 1875, he was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] In 1896, Agassiz visited Fiji and Queensland and inspected the Great Barrier Reef, publishing a paper on the subject in 1898.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] Of Agassiz's other writings on marine zoology, most are contained in the bulletins and memoirs of the museum of comparative zoology.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] However, in 1865, he published with Elizabeth Cary Agassiz, his stepmother, *Seaside Studies in Natural History*, a work at once exact and stimulating.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] They also published, in 1871, *Marine Animals of Massachusetts Bay*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] He received the German Order Pour le Mérite for Science and Arts in August 1902.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] Agassiz also received the Victoria Research Medal, and the Legion of Honour.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] Agassiz served as a president of the National Academy of Sciences, which since 1913 has awarded the Alexander Agassiz Medal in his memory.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] He died in 1910 on board the RMS *Adriatic* en route to New York from Southampton.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] He and his wife Anna Russell (1840–1873) were the parents of three sons – George Russell Agassiz (1861–1951), Maximilian Agassiz (1866–1943) and Rodolphe Louis Agassiz (1871–1933).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] Alexander Agassiz is commemorated in the scientific name of a species of lizard, *Anolis agassizi*, and a fish, *Leptochilichthys agassizii*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] A statue of Alexander Agassiz erected in 1923 is located in Calumet, Michigan, next to his summer home where he stayed while fulfilling his duties as president of the Calumet and Hecla Mining Company.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] The Company Headquarters, Agassiz' statue, and many other buildings and landmarks from the now defunct company are administered and maintained by the Keweenaw National Historical Park, whose headquarters overlook the statue of Agassiz.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] A major building of the Hopkins Marine Station is named after him.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-agassiz] The RV (research vessel) Agassiz is named after him.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Between 1799 and 1804, Humboldt travelled extensively in the Americas, exploring and describing them for the first time from a non-Spanish European scientific point of view.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] His description of the journey was written up and published in several volumes over 21 years.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt resurrected the use of the word *cosmos* from the ancient Greek and assigned it to his multivolume treatise, *Kosmos*, in which he sought to unify diverse branches of scientific knowledge and culture.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] This important work also motivated a holistic perception of the universe as one interacting entity, which introduced concepts of ecology leading to ideas of environmentalism.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] In 1800, and again in 1831, he described scientifically, on the basis of observations generated during his travels, local impacts of development causing human-induced climate change.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt is seen as "the father of ecology" and "the father of environmentalism".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Alexander von Humboldt was born in Berlin in Prussia on 14 September 1769.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] He was baptized as a baby in the Lutheran faith, with the Duke of Brunswick-Wolfenbüttel serving as godfather.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] His father, Alexander Georg von Humboldt (1720–1779), belonged to a prominent German noble family from Pomerania.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Although not one of the titled gentry, he was a major in the Prussian Army, who had served with the Duke of Brunswick.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] At age 42, Alexander Georg was rewarded for his services in the Seven Years' War with the post of royal chamberlain.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] He profited from the contract to lease state lotteries and tobacco sales.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Alexander's grandfather was Johann Paul von Humboldt (1684–1740), who married Sophia Dorothea von Schweder (1688–1749), daughter of Prussian General Adjutant Michael von Schweder (1663–1729).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] In 1766, his father, Alexander Georg married Maria Elisabeth Colomb, a well-educated woman and widow of Baron Friedrich Ernst von Holwede (1723–1765), with whom she had a son Heinrich Friedrich Ludwig (1762–1817).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Alexander Georg and Maria Elisabeth had four children: two daughters, Karoline and Gabriele, who died young, and then two sons, Wilhelm and Alexander.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Her first-born son, Wilhelm and Alexander's half-brother, Rittmaster in the Gendarme regiment was something of a ne'er-do-well, not often mentioned in the family history.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Alexander Georg died in 1779, leaving the brothers Humboldt in the care of their emotionally distant mother.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] She had high ambitions for Alexander and his older brother Wilhelm, hiring excellent tutors, who were Enlightenment thinkers, including Kantian physician Marcus Herz and botanist Carl Ludwig Willdenow, who became one of the most important botanists in Germany.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt's mother expected them to become civil servants of the Prussian state.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] The money left to Alexander's mother by Baron Holwede became instrumental in funding Alexander's explorations after her death; contributing more than 70% of his private income.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Due to his youthful penchant for collecting and labeling plants, shells, and insects, Alexander received the playful title of "the little apothecary".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Marked for a political career, Alexander studied finance for six months in 1787 at the University of Frankfurt (Oder), which his mother might have chosen less for its academic excellence than its closeness to their home in Berlin.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] On 25 April 1789, he matriculated at the University of Göttingen, then known for the lectures of C.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] His brother Wilhelm was already a student at Göttingen, but they did not interact much, since their intellectual interests were quite different.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] His vast and varied interests were by this time fully developed.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] At the University of Göttingen, Humboldt met Steven Jan van Geuns, a Dutch medical student, with whom he travelled to the Rhine in the fall of 1789.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] In Mainz, they met Georg Forster, a naturalist who had been with Captain James Cook on his second voyage.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt's scientific excursion resulted in his 1790 treatise *Mineralogische Beobachtungen über einige Basalte am Rhein* (Brunswick, 1790) (*Mineralogic Observations on Several Basalts on the River Rhine*).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] The following year, 1790, Humboldt returned to Mainz to embark with Forster on a journey to England, Humboldt's first sea voyage, the Netherlands, and France.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] In England, he met Sir Joseph Banks, president of the Royal Society, who had travelled with Captain Cook; Banks showed Humboldt his huge herbarium, with specimens of the South Sea tropics.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] The scientific friendship between Banks and Humboldt lasted until Banks's death in 1820, and the two shared botanical specimens for study.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Banks also mobilized his scientific contacts in later years to aid Humboldt's work.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] In Paris, Humboldt and Forster witnessed the preparations for the Festival of the Federation.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Yet, Humboldt's take on the French Revolution remained ambivalent.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt's passion for travel was of long standing.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] He devoted to prepare himself as a scientific explorer.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] With this emphasis, he studied commerce and foreign languages at Hamburg, geology at Freiberg School of Mines in 1791 under A.G.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Werner, leader of the Neptunist school of geology; from anatomy at Jena under J.C.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Loder; and astronomy and the use of scientific instruments under F.X. von Zach and J.G.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] During this period, his brother Wilhelm married, but Alexander did not attend the nuptials.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt graduated from the Freiberg School of Mines in 1792 and was appointed to a Prussian government position in the Department of Mines as an inspector in Bayreuth and the Fichtel Mountains.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt was excellent at his job, with production of gold ore in his first year outstripping the previous eight years.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] During his period as a mine inspector, Humboldt demonstrated his deep concern for the men laboring in the mines.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] He opened a free school for miners, paid for out of his own pocket, which became an unchartered government training school for labor.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] He also sought to establish an emergency relief fund for miners, aiding them following accidents.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt's researches into the vegetation of the mines of Freiberg led to the publication in Latin (1793) of his *Florae Fribergensis, accedunt Aphorismi ex Doctrina, Physiologiae Chemicae Plantarum*, which was a compendium of his botanical researches.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] That publication brought him to the attention of Johann Wolfgang von Goethe, who had met Humboldt at the family home when Alexander was a boy, but Goethe was now interested in meeting the young scientist to discuss metamorphism of plants.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] An introduction was arranged by Humboldt's brother, who lived in the university town of Jena, not far from Goethe.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Goethe had developed his own extensive theories on comparative anatomy.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Working before Darwin, he believed that animals had an internal force, an *urform*, that gave them a basic shape and then they were further adapted to their environment by an external force.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt urged him to publish his theories.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Together, the two discussed and expanded these ideas.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Goethe and Humboldt soon became close friends.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt often returned to Jena in the years that followed.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Goethe remarked about Humboldt to friends that he had never met anyone so versatile.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt's drive served as an inspiration for Goethe.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] In 1797, Humboldt returned to Jena for three months.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] During this time, Goethe moved from his residence in Weimar to reside in Jena.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Together, Humboldt and Goethe attended university lectures on anatomy and conducted their own experiments.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] One experiment involved hooking up a frog leg to various metals.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] They found no effect until the moisture of Humboldt's breath triggered a reaction that caused the frog leg to leap off the table.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt described this as one of his favorite experiments because it was as if he were "breathing life into" the leg.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] During this visit, a thunderstorm killed a farmer and his wife.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt obtained their corpses and analyzed them in the anatomy tower of the university.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] In 1794, Humboldt was admitted to the famous group of intellectuals and cultural leaders of Weimar Classicism.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Goethe and Schiller were the key figures at the time.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] In 1792 and 1797, Humboldt was in Vienna; in 1795 he made a geological and botanical tour through Switzerland and Italy.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Neither brother attended the funeral of their mother on 19 November 1796.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt had not hidden his aversion to his mother, with one correspondent writing of him after her death, "her death... must be particularly welcomed by you".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] After severing his official connections, he awaited an opportunity to fulfill his long-cherished dream of travel.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt was able to spend more time on writing up his research.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] With the financial resources to fund his scientific travels, he sought a ship on a major expedition.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] In the meantime, he went to Paris, where his brother Wilhelm was living.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Paris was a great center of scientific learning and his brother and sister-in-law Caroline were well connected in those circles.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Louis-Antoine de Bougainville urged Humboldt to accompany him on a major expedition, likely to last five years, but the French revolutionary Directoire placed Nicolas Baudin at the head of it rather than the aging scientific traveler.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] On the postponement of Captain Baudin's proposed voyage of circumnavigation due to continuing warfare in Europe, which Humboldt had been officially invited to accompany, Humboldt was deeply disappointed.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He had already selected scientific instruments for his voyage.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He did, however, have a stroke of luck with meeting Aimé Bonpland, the botanist and physician for the voyage.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Discouraged, the two left Paris for Marseille, where they hoped to join Napoleon Bonaparte in Egypt, but North Africans were in revolt against the French invasion in Egypt and French authorities refused permission to travel.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt and Bonpland eventually found their way to Madrid, where their luck changed spectacularly.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] In Madrid, Humboldt sought authorization to travel to Spain's realms in the Americas; he was aided in obtaining it by the German representative of Saxony at the royal Bourbon court.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Baron Forell had an interest in mineralogy and science endeavors and was inclined to help Humboldt.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] At that time, the Bourbon Reforms sought to reform administration of the realms and revitalize their economies.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] At the same time, the Spanish Enlightenment was in florescence.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] For Humboldt "the confluent effect of the Bourbon revolution in government and the Spanish Enlightenment had created ideal conditions for his venture".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The Bourbon monarchy had already authorized and funded expeditions, with the Botanical Expedition to the Viceroyalty of Peru to Chile and Peru (1777–1788), New Granada (1783–1816), New Spain (Mexico) (1787–1803), and the Malaspina Expedition (1789–1794).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] These were lengthy, state-sponsored enterprises to gather information about plants and animals from the Spanish realms, assess economic possibilities, and provide plants and seeds for the Royal Botanical Garden in Madrid (founded 1755).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] These expeditions took naturalists and artists, who created visual images as well as careful written observations as well as collecting seeds and plants themselves.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Crown officials as early as 1779 issued and systematically distributed *Instructions concerning the most secure and economic means to transport live plants by land and sea from the most distant countries*, with illustrations, including one for the crates to transport seeds and plants.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] When Humboldt requested authorization from the crown to travel to Spanish America, most importantly, with his own financing, it was given positive response.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Spain under the Habsburg monarchy had guarded its realms against foreigner travelers and intruders.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The Bourbon monarch was open to Humboldt's proposal.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Spanish Foreign Minister Don Mariano Luis de Urquijo received the formal proposal and Humboldt was presented to the monarch in March 1799.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt was granted access to crown officials and written documentation on Spain's empire.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] With Humboldt's experience working for the absolutist Prussian monarchy as a government mining official, Humboldt had both the academic training and experience of working well within a bureaucratic structure.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Before leaving Madrid in 1799, Humboldt and Bonpland visited the Natural History Museum, which held results of Martín Sessé y Lacasta and José Mariano Mociño's botanical expedition to New Spain.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt and Bonpland met Hipólito Ruiz López and José Antonio Pavón y Jiménez of the royal expedition to Peru and Chile in person in Madrid and examined their botanical collections.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Armed with authorization from the King of Spain, Humboldt and Bonpland made haste to sail, taking the ship *Pizarro* from La Coruña, on 5 June 1799.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The ship stopped six days on the island of Tenerife, where Humboldt climbed the volcano Teide, and then sailed on to the New World, landing at Cumaná, Venezuela, on 16 July.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The ship's destination was not originally Cumaná, but an outbreak of typhoid on board meant that the captain changed course from Havana to land in northern South America.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt had not mapped out a specific plan of exploration, so that the change did not upend a fixed itinerary.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He later wrote that the diversion to Venezuela made possible his explorations along the Orinoco River to the border of Portuguese Brazil.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] With the diversion, the *Pizarro* encountered two large dugout canoes each carrying 18 Guayaqui Indians.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The *Pizarro*'s captain accepted the offer of one of them to serve as pilot.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt hired this Indian, named Carlos del Pino, as a guide.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] A great deal of information on the new jurisdiction had already been compiled by François de Pons, but was not published until 1806.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] At the invitation of the captain general, Manuel de Guevara y Vasconcelos, Humboldt stayed in Caracas for about two months, leaving in February.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Rather than describe the city and its administration, Humboldt started his researches with the valley of Aragua, where export crops of sugar, coffee, cacao, and cotton were cultivated, visiting a plantation owned by the Bolívar family.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Cacao plantations were the most profitable, as world demand for chocolate rose.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] It is here that Humboldt is said to have developed his idea of human-induced climate change.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Investigating evidence of a rapid fall in the water level of the valley's Lake Valencia, Humboldt credited the desiccation to the clearance of tree cover and to the inability of the exposed soils to retain water.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] With their clear cutting of trees, the agriculturalists were removing the woodland's "threefold" moderating influence upon temperature: cooling shade, evaporation and radiation.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt visited the mission at Caripe and explored the Guácharo cavern, where he found the oilbird, which he was to make known to science as *Steatornis caripensis*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He also described the Guanoco asphalt lake as "The spring of the good priest" ("*Quelle des guten Priesters*").
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Returning to Cumaná, Humboldt observed, on the night of 11–12 November, a remarkable meteor shower (the Leonids).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He proceeded with Bonpland to Caracas where he climbed the Avila mount with the young poet Andrés Bello, the former tutor of Simón Bolívar, who later became the leader of independence in northern South America.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt met the Venezuelan Bolívar himself in 1804 in Paris and spent time with him in Rome.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The documentary record does not support the supposition that Humboldt inspired Bolívar to participate in the struggle for independence, but it does indicate Bolívar's admiration for Humboldt's production of new knowledge on Spanish America.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] In February 1800, Humboldt and Bonpland left the coast with the purpose of exploring the course of the Orinoco River and its tributaries.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This trip, which lasted four months and covered 1,725 miles (2,776 km) of wild and largely uninhabited country, had an aim of establishing the existence of the Casiquiare canal (a communication between the water systems of the rivers Orinoco and Amazon).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Around 19 March 1800, Humboldt and Bonpland discovered dangerous electric eels, whose shock could kill a man.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] To catch them, locals suggested they drive wild horses into the river, which brought the eels out from the river mud, and resulted in a violent confrontation of eels and horses, some of which died.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt and Bonpland captured and dissected some eels, which retained their ability to shock; both received potentially dangerous electric shocks during their investigations.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The encounter made Humboldt think more deeply about electricity and magnetism, typical of his ability to extrapolate from an observation to more general principles.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt returned to the incident in several of his later writings, including his travelogue *Personal Narrative* (1814–29), *Views of Nature* (1807), and *Aspects of Nature* (1849).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Two months later, they explored the territory of the Maipures and that of the then-recently extinct Atures Indians.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt laid to rest the persistent myth of Walter Raleigh's Lake Parime by proposing that the seasonal flooding of the Rupununi savannah had been misidentified as a lake.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] On 24 November 1800, the two friends set sail for Cuba, landing on 19 December, where they met fellow botanist and plant collector John Fraser.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Fraser and his son had been shipwrecked off the Cuban coast, and did not have a license to be in the Spanish Indies.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt, who was already in Cuba, interceded with crown officials in Havana, as well as giving them money and clothing.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Fraser obtained permission to remain in Cuba and explore.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt entrusted Fraser with taking two cases of Humboldt and Bonpland's botanical specimens to England when he returned, for eventual conveyance to the German botanist Willdenow in Berlin.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt and Bonpland stayed in Cuba until 5 March 1801, when they left for the mainland of northern South America again, arriving there on 30 March.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt is considered to be the "second discoverer of Cuba" due to the scientific and social research he conducted on this Spanish colony.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] During an initial three-month stay at Havana, his first tasks were to survey that city properly and the nearby towns of Guanabacoa, Regla, and Bejucal.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He befriended Cuban landowner and thinker Francisco de Arango y Parreño; together they visited the *Guines* area in south Havana, the valleys of Matanzas Province, and the Valley of the Sugar Mills in Trinidad.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Those three areas were, at the time, the first frontier of sugar production in the island.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] During those trips, Humboldt collected statistical information on Cuba's population, production, technology and trade, and with Arango, made suggestions for enhancing them.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He predicted that the agricultural and commercial potential of Cuba was huge and could be vastly improved with proper leadership in the future.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] On their way back to Europe from the Americas, Humboldt and Bonpland stopped again in Cuba, leaving from the port of Veracruz and arriving in Cuba on 7 January 1804, staying until 29 April 1804.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] In Cuba, he collected plant material and made extensive notes.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] During this time, he socialized with his scientific and landowner friends, conducted mineralogical surveys, and finished his vast collection of the island's flora and fauna that he eventually published as *Essai politique sur l'îsle de Cuba*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] After their first stay in Cuba of three months, they returned to the mainland at Cartagena de Indias (now in Colombia), a major center of trade in northern South America.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Ascending the swollen stream of the Magdalena River to Honda, they arrived in Bogotá on 6 July 1801, where they met the Spanish botanist José Celestino Mutis, head of the Royal Botanical Expedition to New Granada, staying there until 8 September 1801.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Mutis was generous with his time and gave Humboldt access to the huge pictorial record he had compiled since 1783.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Mutis was based in Bogotá, but as with other Spanish expeditions, he had access to local knowledge and a workshop of artists, who created highly accurate and detailed images.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This type of careful recording meant that even if specimens were not available to study at a distance, "because the images travelled, the botanists did not have to".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt was astounded at Mutis's accomplishment; when Humboldt published his first volume on botany, he dedicated it to Mutis "as a simple mark of our admiration and acknowledgement".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt had hopes of connecting with the French sailing expedition of Baudin, now finally underway, so Bonpland and Humboldt hurried to Ecuador.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] They crossed the frozen ridges of the Cordillera Real and reached Quito on 6 January 1802, after a tedious and difficult journey.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This was a world record at the time, higher even than had been ascended in a balloon, (for a westerner—Incas had climbed much higher altitudes centuries before), but 1000 feet short of the summit.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt's journey concluded with an expedition to the sources of the Amazon *en route* for Lima, Peru.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] At Callao, the main port for Peru, Humboldt observed the transit of Mercury on 9 November and studied the fertilizing properties of guano, rich in nitrogen, the subsequent introduction of which into Europe was due mainly to his writings.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt and Bonpland had not intended to go to New Spain, but when they were unable to join a voyage to the Pacific, they left the Ecuadorian port of Guayaquil and headed for Acapulco on Mexico's west coast.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Even before Humboldt and Bonpland started on their way to New Spain's capital on Mexico's central plateau, Humboldt realized the captain of the vessel that brought them to Acapulco had reckoned its location incorrectly.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Since Acapulco was the main west-coast port and the terminus of the Asian trade from the Spanish Philippines, having accurate maps of its location was extremely important.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt set up his instruments, surveying the deep-water bay of Acapulco, to determine its longitude.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt and Bonpland landed in Acapulco on 15 February 1803, and from there they went to Taxco, a silver-mining town in modern Guerrero.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] In April 1803, he visited Cuernavaca, Morelos.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Impressed by its climate, he nicknamed the city the *City of Eternal Spring*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt and Bonpland arrived in Mexico City, having been officially welcomed via a letter from the king's representative in New Spain, Viceroy Don José de Iturrigaray.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt was also given a special passport to travel throughout New Spain and letters of introduction to intendants, the highest officials in New Spain's administrative districts (intendancies).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This official aid to Humboldt allowed him to have access to crown records, mines, landed estates, canals, and Mexican antiquities from the prehispanic era.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt read the writings of Bishop-elect of the important diocese of Michoacan Manuel Abad y Queipo, a classical liberal, that were directed to the crown for the improvement of New Spain.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] They spent the year in the viceroyalty, traveling to different Mexican cities in the central plateau and the northern mining region.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The first journey was from Acapulco to Mexico City, through what is now the Mexican state of Guerrero.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The route was suitable only for mule train, and all along the way, Humboldt took measurements of elevation.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] When he left Mexico a year later in 1804, from the east coast port of Veracruz, he took a similar set of measures, which resulted in a chart in the *Political Essay*, the physical plan of Mexico with the dangers of the road from Acapulco to Mexico City, and from Mexico City to Veracruz.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This visual depiction of elevation was part of Humboldt's general insistence that the data he collected be presented in a way more easily understood than statistical charts.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] A great deal of his success in gaining a more general readership for his works was his understanding that "anything that has to do with extent or quantity can be represented geometrically.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Statistical projections [charts and graphs], which speak to the senses without tiring the intellect have the advantage of bringing attention to a large number of important facts".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt was impressed with Mexico City, which at the time was the largest city in the Americas, and one that could be counted as modern.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He declared "no city of the new continent, without even excepting those of the United States, can display such great and solid scientific establishments as the capital of Mexico".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He pointed to the Royal College of Mines, the Royal Botanical Garden and the Royal Academy of San Carlos as exemplars of a metropolitan capital in touch with the latest developments on the continent and insisting on its modernity.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He also recognized important criollo savants in Mexico, including José Antonio de Alzate y Ramírez, who died in 1799, just before Humboldt's visit; Miguel Velásquez de León; and Antonio de León y Gama.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt spent time at the Valenciana silver mine in Guanajuato, central New Spain, at the time the most important in the Spanish empire.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The bicentennial of his visit in Guanajuato was celebrated with a conference at the University of Guanajuato, with Mexican academics highlighting various aspects of his impact on the city.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt could have simply examined the geology of the fabulously rich mine, but he took the opportunity to study the entire mining complex as well as analyze mining statistics of its output.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] His report on silver mining is a major contribution, and considered the strongest and best informed section of his *Political Essay*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Although Humboldt was himself a trained geologist and mining inspector, he drew on mining experts in Mexico.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] One was Fausto Elhuyar, then head of the General Mining Court in Mexico City, who, like Humboldt was trained in Freiberg.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Another was Andrés Manuel del Río, director of Royal College of Mines, whom Humboldt knew when they were both students in Freiberg.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The Bourbon monarchs had established the mining court and the college to elevate mining as a profession, since revenues from silver constituted the crown's largest source of income.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt also consulted other German mining experts, who were already in Mexico.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] While Humboldt was a welcome foreign scientist and mining expert, the Spanish crown had established fertile ground for Humboldt's investigations into mining.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] For Humboldt, a key question was the influence of climate on the development of these civilizations.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] When he published his *Vues des cordillères*, he included a color image of the Aztec calendar stone (which had been discovered in 1790 buried in the main plaza of Mexico City), along with select drawings of the Dresden Codex and others he sought out later in European collections.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] His aim was to muster evidence that these pictorial and sculptural images could allow the reconstruction of prehispanic history.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He sought out Mexican experts in the interpretation of sources from there, especially Antonio Pichardo, who was the literary executor of Antonio de León y Gama's work.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] For American-born Spaniards (criollos) who were seeking sources of pride in Mexico's ancient past, Humboldt's recognition of these ancient works and dissemination in his publications was a boon.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He read the work of exiled Jesuit Francisco Javier Clavijero, which celebrated Mexico's prehispanic civilization, and which Humboldt invoked to counter the pejorative assertions about the new world by Buffon, de Pauw, and Raynal.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt ultimately viewed both the prehispanic realms of Mexico and Peru as despotic and barbaric.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] However, he also drew attention to indigenous monuments and artifacts as cultural productions that had "both ... historical *and* artistic significance".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] One of his most widely read publications resulting from his travels and investigations in Spanish America was the *Essai politique sur le royaum de la Nouvelle Espagne*, quickly translated to English as *Political Essay on the Kingdom of New Spain* (1811).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This treatise was the result of Humboldt's own investigations as well as the generosity of Spanish colonial officials for statistical data.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Leaving from Cuba, Humboldt decided to take an unplanned short visit to the United States.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Knowing that the current U.S. president, Thomas Jefferson, was himself a scientist, Humboldt wrote to him saying that he would be in the United States.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Jefferson warmly replied, inviting him to visit the White House in the nation's new capital.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] In his letter Humboldt had gained Jefferson's interest by mentioning that he had discovered mammoth teeth near the Equator.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Jefferson had previously written that he believed mammoths had never lived so far south.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt had also hinted at his knowledge of New Spain.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt's treatise on cinchona was published in English in 1821.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] After arriving in Washington D.C, Humboldt held numerous intense discussions with Jefferson on both scientific matters and also his year-long stay in New Spain.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Jefferson had only recently concluded the Louisiana Purchase, which now placed New Spain on the southwest border of the United States.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The Spanish minister in Washington, D.C. had declined to furnish the U.S. government with information about Spanish territories, and access to the territories was strictly controlled.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt was able to supply Jefferson with the latest information on the population, trade agriculture and military of New Spain.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This information would later be the basis for his *Essay on the Political Kingdom of New Spain* (1810).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Jefferson was unsure of where the border of the newly-purchased Louisiana was precisely, and Humboldt wrote him a two-page report on the matter.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Jefferson would later refer to Humboldt as "the most scientific man of the age".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Albert Gallatin, Secretary of the Treasury, said of Humboldt "I was delighted and swallowed more information of various kinds in less than two hours than I had for two years past in all I had read or heard." Gallatin, in turn, supplied Humboldt with information he sought on the United States.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] After six weeks, Humboldt set sail for Europe from the mouth of the Delaware and landed at Bordeaux on 3 August 1804.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt kept a detailed diary of his sojourn to Spanish America, running some 4,000 pages, which he drew on directly for his multiple publications following the expedition.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The leather-bound diaries themselves are now in Germany, having been returned from Russia to East Germany, where they were taken by the Red Army after World War II.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Following German reunification, the diaries were returned to a descendant of Humboldt.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] For a time, there was concern about their being sold, but that was averted.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] A government-funded project to digitize the Spanish American expedition as well as his later Russian expedition has been undertaken (2014–2017) by the University of Potsdam and the German State Library–Prussian Cultural Heritage Foundation.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt's decades' long endeavor to publish the results of this expedition not only resulted in multiple volumes, but also made his international reputation in scientific circles.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt came to be well-known with the reading public as well, with popular, densely illustrated, condensed versions of his work in multiple languages.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Bonpland, his fellow scientist and collaborator on the expedition, collected botanical specimens and preserved them, but unlike Humboldt who had a passion to publish, Bonpland had to be prodded to do the formal descriptions.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Many scientific travelers and explorers produced huge visual records which remained unseen by the general public until the late nineteenth century.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] In the case of the Malaspina Expedition, it was not until the late twentieth century when Mutis's botanical, some 12,000 drawings from New Granada, was published.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt, by contrast, published immediately and continuously, using and ultimately exhausting his personal fortune, to produce both scientific and popular texts.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt's name and fame were made by his travels to Spanish America, particularly his publication of the *Political Essay on the Kingdom of New Spain*; his image as the premier European scientist was a later development.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The achievements of the Bourbon regime, especially in New Spain, were evident in the precise data Humboldt systematized and published.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This memorable expedition may be regarded as having laid the foundation of the sciences of physical geography, plant geography, and meteorology.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Key to that was Humboldt's meticulous and systematic measurement of phenomena with the most advanced instruments then available.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He closely observed plant and animal species in situ, not just in isolation, noting all elements in relation to one other.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He collected specimens of plants and animals, dividing the growing collection so that if a portion was lost, other parts might survive.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt saw the need for an approach to science that could account for the harmony of nature among the diversity of the physical world.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] For Humboldt, "the unity of nature" meant that it was the interrelation of all physical sciences—such as the conjoining between biology, meteorology and geology—that determined where specific plants grew.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He found these relationships by unraveling myriad, painstakingly collected data, data extensive enough that it became an enduring foundation upon which others could base their work.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt viewed nature holistically, and tried to explain natural phenomena without the appeal to religious dogma.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He believed in the central importance of observation, and as a consequence had amassed a vast array of the most sophisticated scientific instruments then available.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Each had its own velvet lined box and was the most accurate and portable of its time; nothing quantifiable escaped measurement.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] According to Humboldt, everything should be measured with the finest and most modern instruments and sophisticated techniques available, for that collected data was the basis of all scientific understanding.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This quantitative methodology would become known as Humboldtian science.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt wrote "Nature herself is sublimely eloquent.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The stars as they sparkle in firmament fill us with delight and ecstasy, and yet they all move in orbit marked out with mathematical precision." However, Andreas Daum has recently revisited the concept of Humboldtian Science and set it apart from "Humboldt's science".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] His *Essay on the Geography of Plants* (published first in French and then German, both in 1807) was based on the then novel idea of studying the distribution of organic life as affected by varying physical conditions.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This was most famously depicted in his published cross-section of Chimborazo, approximately two feet by three feet (54 cm × 84 cm) color pictorial, he called *Ein Naturgemälde der Anden* and what is also called the Chimborazo Map.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] It was a fold-out at the back of the publication.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt first sketched the map when he was in South America, which included written descriptions on either side of the cross-section of Chimborazo.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] These detailed the information on temperature, altitude, humidity, atmosphere pressure, and the animal and plants (with their scientific names) found at each elevation.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Plants from the same genus appear at different elevations.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The depiction is on an east-west axis going from the Pacific coast lowlands to the Andean range of which Chimborazo was a part, and the eastern Amazonian basin.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt showed the three zones of coast, mountains, and Amazonia, based on his own observations, but he also drew on existing Spanish sources, particularly Pedro Cieza de León, which he explicitly referred to.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The Spanish American scientist Francisco José de Caldas had also measured and observed mountain environments and had earlier come to similar ideas about environmental factors in the distribution of life forms.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt was thus not putting forward something entirely new, but it is argued that his finding is not derivative either.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The Chimborazo map displayed complex information in an accessible fashion.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The map was the basis for comparison with other major peaks.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] By his delineation (in 1817) of isothermal lines, he at once suggested the idea and devised the means of comparing the climatic conditions of various countries.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This was a major contribution to climatology.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] His discovery of the decrease in intensity of Earth's magnetic field from the poles to the equator was communicated to the Paris Institute in a memoir read by him on 7 December 1804.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Its importance was attested by the speedy emergence of rival claims.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] His services to geology were based on his attentive study of the volcanoes of the Andes and Mexico, which he observed and sketched, climbed, and measured with a variety of instruments.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] By climbing Chimborazo, he established an altitude record which became the basis for measurement of other volcanoes in the Andes and the Himalayas.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] As with other aspects of his investigations, he developed methods to show his synthesized results visually, using the graphic method of geologic-cross sections.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He showed that volcanoes fell naturally into linear groups, presumably corresponding with vast subterranean fissures; and by his demonstration of the igneous origin of rocks previously held to be of aqueous formation, he contributed largely to the elimination of erroneous views, such as Neptunism.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt was a significant contributor to cartography, creating maps, particularly of New Spain, that became the template for later mapmakers in Mexico.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] His careful recording of latitude and longitude led to accurate maps of Mexico, the port of Acapulco, the port of Veracruz, and the Valley of Mexico, and a map showing trade patterns among continents.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] His maps also included schematic information on geography, converting areas of administrative districts (intendancies) using proportional squares.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The U.S. was keen to see his maps and statistics on New Spain, since they had implication for territorial claims following the Louisiana Purchase.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Later in life, Humboldt published three volumes (1836–1839) examining sources that dealt with the early voyages to the Americas, pursuing his interest in nautical astronomy in the fifteenth and sixteenth centuries.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] His research yielded the origin of the name "America", put on a map of the Americas by Martin Waldseemüller.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt conducted a census of the indigenous and European inhabitants in New Spain, publishing a schematized drawing of racial types and populations distribution, grouping them by region and social characteristics.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He estimated the population to be six million individuals.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He estimated Indians to be forty percent of New Spain's population, but their distribution being uneven; the most dense were in the center and south of Mexico, the least dense in the north.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He presented these data in chart form, for easier understanding.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He also surveyed the non-Indian population, categorized as Whites (Spaniards), *Negroes*, and castes (*castas*).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt reported that American-born Spaniards were legally racial equals of those born in Spain, but the crown policy since the Bourbons took the Spanish throne privileged those born in Iberia.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt observed that "the most miserable European, without education and without intellectual cultivation, thinks himself superior to whites born in the new continent".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The truth in this assertion, and the conclusions derived from them, have been often disputed as superficial, or politically motivated, by some authors, considering that between 40% and 60% of high offices in the new world were held by creoles.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The enmity between some creoles and the peninsular-born whites increasingly became an issue in the late period of Spanish rule, with creoles increasingly alienated from the crown.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt's assessment was that royal government abuses and the example of a new model of rule in the United States were eroding the unity of whites in New Spain.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] One scholar says that his writings contain fantastical descriptions of America, while leaving out its inhabitants, stating that Humboldt, coming from the Romantic school of thought, believed '... nature is perfect till man deforms it with care'.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The further assessment is that he largely neglected the human societies amidst nature.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Views of indigenous peoples as 'savage' or 'unimportant' leaves them out of the historical picture.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Other scholars counter that Humboldt dedicated large parts of his work to describing the conditions of slaves, indigenous peoples, mixed-race castas, and society in general.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He often showed his disgust for the slaveryand inhumane conditions in which indigenous peoples and others were treated and he often criticized Spanish colonial policies.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt was not primarily an artist, but he could draw well, allowing him to record a visual record of particular places and their natural environment.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Many of his drawings became the basis for illustrations of his many scientific and general publications.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Artists whom Humboldt influenced, such as Johann Moritz Rugendas, followed in his path and painted the same places Humboldt had visited and recorded, such as the basalt formations in Mexico, which was an illustration in his *Vues des Cordillères*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The editing and publication of the encyclopedic mass of scientific, political and archaeological material that had been collected by him during his absence from Europe was now Humboldt's most urgent desire.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] After a short trip to Italy with Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac for the purpose of investigating the law of magnetic declination and a stay of two and a half years in Berlin, in the spring of 1808, he settled in Paris.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] His purpose for being located there was to secure the scientific cooperation required for bringing his great work through the press.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This colossal task, which he at first hoped would occupy but two years, eventually cost him twenty-one, and even then it remained incomplete.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] During his lifetime Humboldt became one of the most famous men in Europe.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Academies, both native and foreign, were eager to elect him to their membership, the first being The American Philosophical Society in Philadelphia, which he visited at the tail end of his travel through the Americas.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He was elected to the Prussian Academy of Sciences in 1805.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He was elected a foreign member of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences in 1810.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The Royal Society, whose president Sir Joseph Banks had aided Humboldt as a young man, now welcomed him as a foreign member.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] After Mexican independence from Spain in 1821, the Mexican government recognized him with high honors for his services to the nation.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] In 1827, the first President of Mexico, Guadalupe Victoria granted Humboldt Mexican citizenship and in 1859, the President of Mexico, Benito Juárez, named Humboldt a hero of the nation (*benemérito de la nación*).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The gestures were purely honorary; he never returned to the Americas following his expedition.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Importantly for Humboldt's long-term financial stability, King Frederick William III of Prussia conferred upon him the honor of the post of royal chamberlain, without at the time exacting the duties.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The appointment had a pension of 2,500 thalers, afterwards doubled.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This official stipend became his main source of income in later years when he exhausted his fortune on the publications of his research.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Financial necessity forced his permanent relocation to Berlin in 1827 from Paris.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] In Paris he found not only scientific sympathy, but the social stimulus which his vigorous and healthy mind eagerly craved.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He was equally in his element as the lion of the salons and as the savant of the Institut de France and the observatory.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] On 12 May 1827 he settled permanently in Berlin, where his first efforts were directed towards the furtherance of the science of terrestrial magnetism.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] In 1827, he began giving public lectures in Berlin, which became the basis for his last major publication, *Kosmos* (1845–1862).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] For many years, it had been one of his favorite schemes to secure, by means of simultaneous observations at distant points, a thorough investigation of the nature and law of "magnetic storms" (a term invented by him to designate abnormal disturbances of Earth's magnetism).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The meeting at Berlin, on 18 September 1828, of a newly formed scientific association, of which he was elected president, gave him the opportunity of setting on foot an extensive system of research in combination with his diligent personal observations.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] His appeal to the Russian government, in 1829, led to the establishment of a line of magnetic and meteorological stations across northern Asia.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Meanwhile, his letter to the Duke of Sussex, then (April 1836) president of the Royal Society, secured for the undertaking, the wide basis of the British dominions.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The *Encyclopædia Britannica*, Eleventh Edition, observes, "Thus that scientific conspiracy of nations which is one of the noblest fruits of modern civilization was by his exertions first successfully organized".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] However, earlier examples of international scientific cooperation exist, notably the 18th-century observations of the transits of Venus.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] In 1856, U.S. diplomat John Bigelow published *Memoir of the Life and Public Services of John Charles Fremont*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] In 1869, the 100th year of his birth, Humboldt's fame was so great that cities all over America celebrated his birth with large festivals.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] In New York City, a bust of his head was unveiled in Central Park.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Scholars have speculated about the reasons for Humboldt's declining renown among the public.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] In 1811, and again in 1818, projects of Asiatic exploration were proposed to Humboldt, first by Tsar Nicholas I's Russian government, and afterwards by the Prussian government; but on each occasion, untoward circumstances interposed.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] It was not until he had begun his sixtieth year that he resumed his early role of traveler in the interests of science.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The Russian Finance Minister, Count Georg von Cancrin, contacted Humboldt about whether a platinum-based currency was possible in Russia and invited him to visit the Ural Mountains.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt was not encouraging about a platinum-based currency, when silver was the standard as a world currency.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] But the invitation to visit the Urals was intriguing, especially since Humboldt had long dreamed of going to Asia.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] He had wanted to travel to India and made considerable efforts to persuade the British East India Company to authorize a trip, but those efforts were fruitless.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] When Russia renewed its earlier invitation to Humboldt, he accepted.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The Russians sought to entice Humboldt by engaging his enduring interest in mining sites, for comparative scientific purposes for Humboldt, but for the Russians to gain expert knowledge about their resources.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] For Humboldt, the Russian monarch's promise to fund the trip was extremely important, since Humboldt's inherited 100,000 thaler fortune was gone and he lived on the Prussian government pension of 2,500–3,000 thalers as the monarch's chamberlain.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The Russian government gave an advance of 1200 *chervontsev* in Berlin and another 20,000 when he arrived in Saint Petersburg.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt was eager to travel not just to the Urals, but also across the steppes of Siberia to Russia's border with China.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt wrote Cancrin saying that he intended to learn Russian to read mining journals in the language.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] As the details of the expedition were worked out, Humboldt said that he would travel to Russia in his own French coach, with a German servant, as well as Gustav Rose, a professor of chemistry and mineralogy.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] He also invited Christian Gottfried Ehrenberg to join the expedition, to study water micro-organisms in Lake Baikal and the Caspian Sea.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt himself was keen to continue his studies of magnetism of mountains and mineral deposits.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] As was usual for his research, he brought scientific instruments to take the most accurate measurements.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The Russians organized the local arrangements, including lodging, horses, accompanying crew.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt's title for the expedition was as an official of the Department of Mines.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] As the expedition neared dangerous areas, he had to travel in a convoy with an escort.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Physically Humboldt was in good condition, despite his advancing years, writing to Cancrin "I still walk very lightly on foot, nine to ten hours without resting, despite my age and my white hair".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Between May and November 1829 he and the growing expedition traversed the wide expanse of the Russian empire from the Neva to the Yenisei, accomplishing in twenty-five weeks a distance of 9,614 miles (15,472 km).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt and the expedition party travelled by coach on well maintained roads, with rapid progress being made because of changes of horses at way stations.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The party had grown, with Johann Seifert, who was a huntsman and collector of animal specimens; a Russian mining official; Count Adolphe Polier, one of Humboldt's friends from Paris; a cook; plus a contingent of Cossacks for security.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Three carriages were filled with people, supplies, and scientific instruments.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] For Humboldt's magnetic readings to be accurate, they carried an iron-free tent.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] This expedition was unlike his Spanish American travels with Bonpland, with the two alone and sometimes accompanied by local guides.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The Russian government was interested in Humboldt's finding prospects for mining and commercial advancement of the realm and made it clear that Humboldt was not to investigate social issues, nor criticize social conditions of Russian serfs.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] In his publications on Spanish America, he did comment on the conditions of the indigenous populations, and deplored black slavery, but well after he had left those territories.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] As Humboldt discovered, the government kept tight control of the expedition, even when it was 1,000 miles (1,600 km) from Moscow, with local government officials greeting the expedition at every stop.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The itinerary was planned with Tobolsk the farthest destination, then a return to Saint Petersburg.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt wrote to the Russian Minister Cancrin that he was extending his travel, knowing that the missive would not reach him in time to scuttle the plan.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The further east he journeyed into wilder territory, the more Humboldt enjoyed it.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] They still followed the Siberian Highway and made excellent progress, sometimes a hundred miles (160 km) in a day.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Although they were halted at the end of July and warned of an anthrax outbreak, Humboldt decided to continue despite the danger.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] "At my age, nothing should be postponed".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The journey though carried out with all the advantages afforded by the immediate patronage of the Russian government, was too rapid to be profitable scientifically.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The correction of the prevalent exaggerated estimate of the height of the Central Asian plateau, and the prediction of the discovery of diamonds in the gold-washings of the Urals, were important aspects of these travels.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] In the end, the expedition took 8 months, travelled 15,500 km, stopped at 658 post stations, and used 12,244 horses.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] One writer claims that "Nothing was quite as Humboldt wanted it.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The entire expedition was a compromise." The Russian emperor offered Humboldt an invitation to return to Russia, but Humboldt declined, due to his disapproval of Nicholas's restrictions on his freedom of movement during the expedition and his ability to freely report on it.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt published two works on the Russian expedition, first *Fragments de géologie et de climatologie asiatiques* in 1831, based on lectures he gave on the topic.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] In 1843, he completed the three-volume *Asie Centrale*, which he dedicated to Tsar Nicholas, which he called "an unavoidable step, as the expedition was accomplished at his expense".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] As of 2016, these works have not been translated to English.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] His 1829 expedition to Russia when he was an old man is much less known than his five-year travels in Spanish America, which had resulted in many published volumes over the decades since his 1804 return.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Nevertheless, it gave Humboldt comparative data for his various later scientific publications.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The first two volumes of the *Kosmos* were published between the years 1845 and 1847 and were intended to comprise the entire work, but Humboldt published three more volumes, one of which was posthumous.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt had long aimed to write a comprehensive work about geography and the natural sciences.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The work attempted to unify the sciences then known in a Kantian framework.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] With inspiration from German Romanticism, Humboldt sought to create a compendium of the world's environment.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] He spent the last decade of his long life—as he called them, his "improbable" years—continuing this work.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The third and fourth volumes were published in 1850–1858; a fragment of a fifth appeared posthumously in 1862.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] His reputation had long since been made with his publications on the Spanish American expedition.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] There is not a consensus on the importance of *Kosmos*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] One scholar, who stresses the importance of Humboldt's *Political Essay on the Kingdom of New Spain* as essential reading, dismisses *Kosmos* as "little more than an academic curiosity".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] A different opinion is that *Kosmos* was his "most influential book".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] As with most of Humboldt's works, *Kosmos* was also translated into multiple languages in editions of uneven quality.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] It was very popular in Britain and America.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] In 1849 a German newspaper commented that in England two of the three different translations were made by women, "while in Germany most of the men do not understand it".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The first translation by Augustin Pritchard—published anonymously by Mr.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Baillière (volume I in 1845 and volume II in 1848)—suffered from being hurriedly made.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] In a letter Humboldt said of it: "It will damage my reputation.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The other two translations were made by Elizabeth Juliana Leeves Sabine under the superintendence of her husband Col.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Edward Sabine (4 volumes 1846–1858), and by Elise Otté (5 volumes 1849–1858, the only complete translation of the 4 German volumes).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] These three translations were also published in the United States.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The numbering of the volumes differs between the German and the English editions.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Volume 3 of the German edition corresponds to the volumes 3 and 4 of the English translation, as the German volume appeared in 2 parts in 1850 and 1851.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Volume 5 of the German edition was not translated until 1981, again by a woman.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Otté's translation benefited from a detailed table of contents, and an index for every volume; of the German edition only volumes 4 and 5 had (extremely short) tables of contents, and the index to the whole work only appeared with volume 5 in 1862.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Less well known in Germany is the atlas belonging to the German edition of the Cosmos *"Berghaus' Physikalischer Atlas"*, better known as the pirated version by Traugott Bromme under the title *"Atlas zu Alexander von Humboldt's Kosmos"* (Stuttgart 1861).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] In Britain, Heinrich Berghaus planned to publish together with Alexander Keith Johnston a *"Physical Atlas"*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] But later Johnston published it alone under the title *"The Physical Atlas of Natural Phenomena"*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] In Britain its connection to the *Cosmos* seems not have been recognized.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Alexander von Humboldt published prolifically throughout his life.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Many works were published originally in French or German, then translated to other languages, sometimes with competing translation editions.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt himself did not keep track of all the various editions.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] He wrote specialized works on particular topics of botany, zoology, astronomy, mineralogy, among others, but he also wrote general works that attracted a wide readership, especially his *Personal Narrative of Travels to the Equinoctial Regions of the New Continent during the years 1799–1804*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] His *Political Essay on the Kingdom of New Spain* was widely read in Mexico itself, the United States, as well as in Europe.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Many of the original works have been digitally scanned by the Biodiversity Heritage Library.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] There have been new editions of print works, including his *Views of the Cordilleras and Monuments of the Indigenous Peoples of the Americas* (2014), which includes reproductions of all the color and black and white plates.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] In the original edition, the publication was in a large format and quite expensive.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] There is a 2009 translation of his *Geography of Plants* and a 2014 English edition of *Views of Nature*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt was generous toward his friends and mentored young scientists.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] He and Bonpland parted ways after their return to Europe, and Humboldt largely took on the task of publishing the results of their Latin American expedition at Humboldt's expense, but he included Bonpland as co-author on the nearly 30 published volumes.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Bonpland returned to Latin America, settling in Buenos Aires, Argentina, then moved to the countryside near the border with Paraguay.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] José Gaspar Rodríguez de Francia, the strong man of Paraguay, abducted Bonpland after killing Bonpland's estate workers.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Bonpland was accused of "agricultural espionage" and of threatening Paraguay's virtual monopoly on the cultivation of yerba mate.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Despite international pressure, including the British government and Simón Bolívar's, along with European scientists including Humboldt, Francia kept Bonpland prisoner until 1831.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] He was released after nearly 10 years in Paraguay.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt and Bonpland maintained a warm correspondence about science and politics until Bonpland's death in 1858.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] During Humboldt's time in Paris, he met in 1818 the young and brilliant Peruvian student of the Royal Mining School of Paris, Mariano Eduardo de Rivero y Ustariz.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Subsequently, Humboldt acted as a mentor of the career of this promising Peruvian scientist.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Another recipient of Humboldt's aid was Louis Agassiz (1807–1873), who was directly aided with needed cash from Humboldt, assistance in securing an academic position, and help with getting his research on zoology published.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Agassiz sent him copies of his publications and went on to gain considerable scientific recognition as a professor at Harvard.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Agassiz delivered an address to the Boston Society of Natural History in 1869, on the centenary of his patron's birth.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] When Humboldt was an elderly man, he aided another young scholar, Gotthold Eisenstein, a brilliant, young, Jewish mathematician in Berlin, for whom he obtained a small crown pension and whom he nominated for the Academy of Science.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt's popular writings inspired many scientists and naturalists, including Charles Darwin, Henry David Thoreau, John Muir, George Perkins Marsh, Ernst Haeckel, Ida Laura Pfeiffer as well as brothers Richard and Robert Schomburgk and Robert, Adolf, and Hermann Schlagintweit.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt carried on correspondence with many contemporaries and two volumes of letters to Karl August Varnhagen von Ense have been published.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Charles Darwin made frequent reference to Humboldt's work in his *Voyage of the Beagle*, where Darwin described his own scientific exploration of the Americas.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] In one note, he placed Humboldt first on the "list of American travellers".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Darwin's work was influenced by Humboldt's writing style as well.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Darwin's sister remarked to him "you had, probably from reading so much of Humboldt, got his phraseology and the kind of flowery French expressions he uses".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] When Darwin's *Journal* was published, he sent a copy to Humboldt, who responded, "You told me in your kind letter that, when you were young, the manner in which I studied and depicted nature in the torrid zones contributed toward exciting in you the ardour and desire to travel in distant lands.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt would later reveal to Darwin in the 1840s that he had been deeply interested in Darwin's grandfather's poetry.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Erasmus Darwin had published the poem *The Loves of the Plants* in the early 1800s.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt praised the poem for combining nature and imagination, a theme that permeated Humboldt's own work.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] A number of nineteenth-century artists travelled to Latin America, following in the footsteps of Humboldt, painting landscapes and scenes of everyday life.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Johann Moritz Rugendas, Ferdinand Bellermann, and Eduard Hildebrandt were three important European painters.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Frederic Edwin Church was the most famous landscape painter in the U.S. in the nineteenth century.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] His paintings of Andean volcanoes that Humboldt climbed helped make Church's reputation.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] His 5 foot by 10 foot painting entitled *The Heart of the Andes* "caused a sensation" when it was completed.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Church had hoped to ship the painting to Berlin to show the painting to Humboldt, but Humboldt died a few days after Church's letter was written.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Church painted Cotopaxi three times, twice in 1855 and then in 1859 in eruption.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] George Catlin, most famous for his portraits of North American Indians and paintings of life among various North American tribes, also travelled to South America, producing a number of paintings.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] He wrote to Humboldt in 1855, sending him his proposal for South American travels.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt replied, thanking him and sending a memorandum helping guide his travels.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Ida Laura Pfeiffer, one of the first female travelers who completed two trips around the world from 1846 to 1855, followed in Humboldt's footsteps.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The two explorers met in Berlin in 1851 before Pfeiffer's second tour and again in 1855 when she returned to Europe.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] In the Napoleonic wars, Prussia had capitulated to France, signing the Treaty of Tilsit.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The Prussian royal family returned to Berlin, but sought better terms of the treaty and Friedrich Wilhelm III commissioned his younger brother Prince Wilhelm with this.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Friedrich Wilhelm III asked Alexander to be part of the mission, charged with introducing the prince to Paris society.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] This turn of events for Humboldt could not have been better, since he desired to live in Paris rather than Berlin.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] In 1814 Humboldt accompanied the allied sovereigns to London.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Three years later he was summoned by the king of Prussia to attend him at the congress of Aachen.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Again in the autumn of 1822 he accompanied the same monarch to the Congress of Verona, proceeded thence with the royal party to Rome and Naples and returned to Paris in the spring of 1823.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt had long regarded Paris as his true home.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Thus, when at last he received from his sovereign a summons to join his court at Berlin, he obeyed reluctantly.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Between 1830 and 1848 Humboldt was frequently employed in diplomatic missions to the court of King Louis Philippe of France, with whom he always maintained the most cordial personal relations.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Charles X of France had been overthrown, with Louis-Philippe of the house of Orléans becoming king.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt knew the family, and he was sent by the Prussian monarch to Paris to report on events to his monarch.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] He spent three years in France, from 1830 to 1833.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] His friends François Arago and François Guizot, were appointed to posts in Louis-Philippe's government.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt's brother, Wilhelm, died on 8 April 1835.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Alexander lamented that he had lost half of himself with the death of his brother.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Upon the accession of the crown prince Frederick William IV in June 1840, Humboldt's favor at court increased.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Indeed, the new king's craving for Humboldt's company became at times so importunate as to leave him only a few waking hours to work on his writing.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt's publications such as *Personal Narrative of Travels to the Equinoctial Regions of the New Continent during the years 1799–1804* originate from a time when colonialism was prevalent.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Within recent academic publications, there are arguments for and against Humboldt's own imperial bias.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Within the book *Imperial Eyes*, Pratt argues for an implicit imperial bias within Humboldt's writing.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] While Humboldt financed his expedition to the Spanish colonies independently, the Spanish monarchy allowed him to travel to South America.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Due to unrest within the Spanish colonies in South America, the Spanish crown implemented liberal reforms which led to greater support of the Spanish monarchy within the lower class.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] However, Pratt points out that the reforms created opposition towards the Spanish rule within the upper class as the declining control of the Spanish monarchy would result in the white South American elite losing their privileges.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] When Humboldt wrote about the natural world within South America, he portrayed it as neutral and free of people: If the indigenous population was mentioned within Humboldt's writing, Pratt argues, they were only represented when they were beneficial for Europeans.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Others argue that Humboldt was a German Columbus, as he described a virginal country that could be used for commerce by Europeans.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Other scholars counter Pratt's argumentation and refer to the abolitionist and anti-colonialist standpoint that Humboldt represents within his writing.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] An example is Humboldt's descriptions of the South American colonies in which he critiqued Spanish colonial rule.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] His close relationship with Enlightenment values such as liberty and freedom led to his support of democracy and his subsequent support of the independence of South America.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] In order to improve the material and political situation of the indigenous population, Humboldt included propositions within his writing that he also presented to the Spanish monarchy.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] When witnessing a slave market, Humboldt was shocked by the treatment of black people which led him to become opposed to slavery and support the abolitionist movement throughout his life.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Within his descriptions in *Personal Narratives*, Humboldt also included the answers that were given to him by indigenous people.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Additionally, Lubrich argues that despite the colonial and orientalist notions of his writing, Humboldt did not recreate these stereotypes, but deconstructed them.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Because Humboldt did not mention God in his work *Cosmos*, and sometimes spoke unfavourably of religious attitudes, it was occasionally speculated that he was a materialist philosopher, or perhaps an atheist.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] However, unlike irreligious figures such as Robert G.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Ingersoll, who went so far as to use Humboldtian science to campaign against religion, Humboldt himself denied imputations of atheism.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] In a letter to Varnhagen von Ense he emphasized that he believed the world had indeed been created, writing of *Cosmos*: "...
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] 'creation' and the 'created world' are never lost sight of in the book.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] It has been argued that "although Humboldt emphasizes the basis of morality in the nature of man, he does acknowledge that a belief in God is linked directly to acts of virtue" and therefore "the dignity of man lies at the centre of Humboldt's religious thought".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt also believed firmly in an afterlife.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt remained distant of organized religion, typical of a Protestant in Germany relating to the Catholic Church; Humboldt held deep respect for the ideal side of religious belief and church life within human communities.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] He differentiated between "negative" religions, and those "all positive religions [which] consist of three distinct parts—a code of morals which is nearly the same in all of them, and generally very pure; a geological chimera, and a myth or a little historical novel".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt showed religious tolerance towards Judaism, and he criticized the political *Jews Bill*, which was an initiative intended to establish legal discrimination against Jews.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] He called this an "abominable" law, since he hoped to see Jews being treated equally in society.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Much of Humboldt's private life remains a mystery because he destroyed his private letters.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] While a gregarious personality, he may have harbored a sense of social alienation, which drove his passion for escape through travel.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt never married: while he was friendly with a number of women, including Henriette, the wife of his mentor Marcus Herz, his sister-in-law Caroline von Humboldt stated "nothing will ever have a great influence on Alexander that doesn't come through men".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] He had many strong male friendships, and at times had romances with men.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] As a student he became infatuated with Wilhelm Gabriel Wegener, a theology student, penning a succession of letters expressing his "fervent love".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] At 25 he met Reinhardt von Haeften (1772–1803), a 22-year-old lieutenant, with whom he lived and travelled for two years, and to whom he wrote in 1794: "I only live through you, my good precious Reinhardt".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] When von Haeften became engaged, Humboldt begged to remain living with him and his wife: "Even if you must refuse me, treat me coldly with disdain, I should still want to be with you... the love I have for you is not just friendship or brotherly love, it is veneration".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] A traveling companion in the Americas for five years was Aimé Bonpland, and in Quito in 1802 he met the Ecuadorian aristocrat Don Carlos Montúfar, who travelled with Humboldt to Europe and lived with him.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] In France, Humboldt travelled and lived with the physicist and balloonist Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Later he had a deep friendship with the married French astronomer François Arago, whom he met daily for 15 years.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt once wrote "I don't know sensual needs".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt inherited a significant fortune, but the expense of his travels, and most especially of publishing (thirty volumes in all), had by 1834 made him totally reliant on the pension of King Frederick William III.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Although he preferred living in Paris, by 1836 the King had insisted he return to Germany.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] He lived with the Court at Sanssouci, and latterly in Berlin, with his valet Seifert, who had accompanied him to Russia in 1829.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Four years before his death, Humboldt executed a deed of gift transferring his entire estate to Seifert, who had by then married and set up a household near Humboldt's apartment.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt had become godfather to his daughter.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The scale of the bequest has always drawn speculation, especially as Seifert was some thirty years younger, and introducing lower class partners into households under the guise of servants was then a common practice.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] In 1908, the sexual researcher Paul Näcke gathered reminiscences from homosexuals including Humboldt's friend the botanist Carl Bolle, then nearly 90 years old: some of the material was incorporated by Magnus Hirschfeld into his 1914 study *Homosexuality in Men and Women*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] However, speculations about Humboldt's private life and possible homosexuality continue to remain a fractious issue among scholars, particularly as earlier biographers had portrayed him as "a largely asexual, Christ-like Humboldt figure ... suitable as a national idol".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] On 24 February 1857, Humboldt suffered a minor stroke, which passed without perceptible symptoms.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] It was not until the winter of 1858–1859 that his strength began to decline; on 6 May 1859, he died peacefully in Berlin, aged 89.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] His last words were reported to be "How glorious these sunbeams are!
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] They seem to call Earth to the Heavens!" His remains were conveyed in state through the streets of Berlin, in a hearse drawn by six horses.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Royal chamberlains led the cortège, each charged with carrying a pillow with Humboldt's medals and other decorations of honor.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt's extended family, descendants of his brother Wilhelm, walked in the procession.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt's coffin was received by the prince-regent at the door of the cathedral.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] He was interred at the family resting-place at Tegel, alongside his brother Wilhelm and sister-in-law Caroline.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The honours which had been showered on Humboldt during their life continued after his death.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] More species are named after Humboldt than after any other human being.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The first centenary of Humboldt's birth was celebrated on 14 September 1869, with great enthusiasm in both the New and Old Worlds.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Numerous monuments were constructed in his honour, such as Humboldt Park in Chicago, planned that year and constructed shortly after the Chicago fire.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Newly explored regions and species named after Humboldt, as discussed below, also stand as a measure of his wide fame and popularity.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] "Scarcely was there a European order which Humboldt had not the right to wear", and "more than a hundred and fifty societies to which he had been elected".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt described many geographical features and species that were hitherto unknown to Europeans.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The mineral humboldtine was named for Alexander by Mariano de Rivero in 1821.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Alexander von Humboldt also lends his name to a prominent lecture series in Human geography in the Netherlands (hosted by the Radboud University Nijmegen).
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] It is the Dutch equivalent of the widely known annual Hettner lectures at the University of Heidelberg.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] After his death, Humboldt's friends and colleagues created the Alexander von Humboldt Foundation (*Stiftung* in German) to continue his generous support of young academics.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Although the original endowment was lost in the German hyperinflation of the 1920s, and again as a result of World War II, the Foundation has been re-endowed by the German government to award young academics and distinguished senior academics from abroad.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] It plays an important role in attracting foreign researchers to work in Germany and enabling German researchers to work abroad for a period.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Edgar Allan Poe dedicated his last major work, *Eureka: A Prose Poem*, to Humboldt, "With Very Profound Respect".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Humboldt's attempt to unify the sciences in his *Kosmos* was a major inspiration for Poe's project.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] In 2019, Josefina Benedetti composed *Humboldt* an Orchestral Suite in five movements.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] The Jan De Nul Group operates a hopper dredger built in 1998 also named *Alexander von Humboldt*.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Simón Bolívar wrote that "The real discoverer of South America was Humboldt, since his work was more useful for our people than the work of all conquerors".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Charles Darwin expressed his debt to Humboldt, and admiration for his work, writing to Joseph Dalton Hooker that Humboldt was the "*greatest scientific traveller who ever lived*".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Wilhelm von Humboldt wrote that "Alexander is destined to combine ideas and follow chains of thoughts which would otherwise have remained unknown for ages.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] His depth, his sharp mind and his incredible speed are a rare combination." Johann Wolfgang Goethe observed that "Humboldt showers us with true treasures".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Friedrich Schiller wrote that "Alexander impresses many, particularly when compared to his brother—because he shows off more!" José de la Luz y Caballero wrote that "Columbus gave Europe a New World; Humboldt made it known in its physical, material, intellectual, and moral aspects".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Napoléon Bonaparte remarked "You have been studying Botanics?
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Just like my wife!" Claude Louis Berthollet said "This man is as knowledgeable as a whole academy".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Thomas Jefferson remarked "I consider him the most important scientist whom I have met".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Emil du Bois-Reymond wrote that "Every assiduous scholar ... is Humboldt's son; we are all his family." Robert G.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Ingersoll wrote that "He was to science what Shakespeare was to the drama".
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/alexander-von-humboldt-p03] Hermann von Helmholtz wrote that "During the first half of the present century we had an Alexander von Humboldt, who was able to scan the scientific knowledge of his time in its details, and to bring it within one vast generalization.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The **American Academy of Arts and Sciences** (**The Academy**) is one of the oldest learned societies in the United States.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It was founded in 1780 during the American Revolution by John Adams, John Hancock, James Bowdoin, Andrew Oliver, and other Founding Fathers of the United States.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is headquartered in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Membership in the academy is achieved through a nominating petition, review, and election process.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy's quarterly journal, *Dædalus*, is published by the MIT Press on behalf of the academy, and has been open-access since January 2021.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy also conducts multidisciplinary public policy research.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Patton has served as President of the Academy since January 2025.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The first class of new members, chosen by the Academy in 1781, included Benjamin Franklin and George Washington as well as several international honorary members.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The initial volume of Academy *Memoirs* appeared in 1785, and the *Proceedings* followed in 1846.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the 1950s, the Academy launched its journal *Daedalus*, reflecting its commitment to a broader intellectual and socially-oriented program.
[src:american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Since the second half of the twentieth century, independent research has become a central focus of the Academy.
